<HTML><head><title> Court TV Law Center Q & A</title></head><BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff VLINK=FF0005><P align=center><img width=400 height=60 src=/graphics/ctv/qanda/qanda3.gif></P>

<CENTER><h2>Legal Information for Family Businesses</h2>

<H3>With Parry Aftab and Nancy Savitt</H3></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/qanda/aftab.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=ABSTOP WIDTH="130" HEIGHT="165" BORDER="0"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/qanda/savitt.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT ALIGN=ABSTOP WIDTH="130" HEIGHT="165" BORDER="0"><P ALIGN=CENTER>The firm of Aftab & Savitt, P.C. specializes in U.S. and international business law. It maintains offices in New York, New Jersey and Russia. The firm serves as outside general counsel to many family-owned businesses and legal advisors to many others. The firm's <a href=http://www.aftab.com/>website</a> features actual cases that illustrate how proper advance planning could have saved successful family businesses  destroyed by infighting.<BR CLEAR=ALL></P>
<A NAME="contents"></A>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#1">What is a family business?</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="#2">Are the legal needs of family businesses different from those of any other business?</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="#3">How else are family businesses different from their counterparts?</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="#4">What can family businesses do to protect themselves against family members (or their ex-spouses) trying to destroy the business?</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="#5">What is the single most important legal issue faced a family business?</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="#6">Are there consultants and advisors specializing in family business to help balance the competing roles or family member and business associate?</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="#7">Are things improving for family businesses with all this information available to them?</A>
</UL>
<PRE>

</PRE>
<A NAME="1"><b>What is a family business?</b></A><BR>
(<A HREF="#contents">Back to Contents</A>)<p>
People differ as to how they define family businesses. We define them as businesses controlled by family members or a family member and which employs one or more family members. They are privately-held and notwithstanding their ownership, can be very large and very profitable. <p>

It has been estimated that there are  more than 12 million U.S. family businesses which account for more than half of the U.S. gross domestic product. <p>

<A NAME="2"><b>Are the legal needs of family businesses different from those of any other business?</b></A><BR>
(<A HREF="#contents">Back to Contents</A>)<p>
Yes and no. A family business is still a business. They have the same problems that all businesses experience-- competition, financing, profitability, understanding a worldwide economy and its impact on businesses of any size, labor and resources and others unique to  them. That's why a good family business lawyer must first be a good business lawyer.<p>

Because family businesses rely heavily on family members for key officer positions, they have fewer problems, if things are running well, with loyalty, management and strategic planning. The key point is "if things are running well." If they are not, everything breaks down at once, the family and the business. Family businesses are like the little girl in the nursery rhyme, "when she was good she was very, very good and when she was bad she was horrid."<p>

Unfortunately, unlike most other businesses, family businesses typically avoid formalizing their management and transition plans. Because of this, the biggest problems faced by family businesses include transition and estate planning, and disputes over management styles and ownership. Sometimes these problems are aggravated by multi-generational issues, such as marriage and divorce of off-spring (or increasingly, divorces and remarriage of the parent(s) who run the business). Sometimes the remarriage or divorce of the family business leader or his or her death or disability can cripple a business beyond repair. <p>

A good family business lawyer needs to understand this, and be able to deal with the multitude of legal issues which develop from these intermingled and often conflicting business and personal relationships. <p>

Just think about the problems and confusion which could result from a younger daughter, who is running the family business, having to tell her father that customers have complained about his responsiveness, or telling her mother that the financials she prepared don't comply with the bank's request. Or what about the wife who feels her husband is carrying the weight of the family business without sufficient recognition and compensation? This gives you just a taste of the kind of confusing  interaction that occurs daily in a family business. There's always a confusion of roles: are you the family member (within a defined pecking order) or the employee-manager-owner (within another defined pecking order)?<p>

These problems are multiplied when the younger generation marries. Often, even if the siblings have worked out their roles satisfactorily, now new members to the family are providing input, and often criticism. Daughters-in-law and sons-in-law  are frequently the cause of family
business breakups. In addition, the family often brings these spouses into the business. Upon divorce of the family member, the former spouse-employee often asserts a claim to a portion of the business. Even when that doesn't happen, the former spouse is most likely out of a job, which certainly hurts that individual and probably the business as well. <p>

<A NAME="3"><b>How else are family businesses different from their counterparts?</b></A><BR>
(<A HREF="#contents">Back to Contents</A>)<p>

The Mass Mutual survey of more than 1,000 family-owned businesses discloses some interesting information about family businesses.<p>

The persons responding to the survey indicated that male relatives are more likely than female relatives to be involved in the family businesses, to hold more influential positions, and to be identified as the key decision-makers for the business. Results disclosed that sons are four times as likely as daughters to be identified by owners as controlling ownership and governance decisions in the next generation.<p>

It is also interesting to note that approximately two-thirds of the people who own family businesses were raised in families that owned a business, and three-quarters of all owners with children said they would encourage their kids to follow in their footsteps. <p>

Family businesses are regularly managed differently from their non-family counterparts as well. Decisions on key issues are made by a small number of people who come to their decisions through consensus. However, most owners feel the key decision makers in the business trust one another, but are less certain they share goals or achieve what they set out to accomplish. (This is a prime reason for careful and clear documentation and advance planning for the business transition and management.)<p>

Finally, the survey results how that family businesses focus on long-term goals, and not on growth for growth's sake. Value and profitability consistently, throughout the years the survey has been conducted, stand out as the top priorities of family business owners, while growth once again ranked considerably lower among financial considerations.<p>

More information about the survey can be obtained from <a href=http://www.mass.mutual.com/familt2.html>Mass Mutual's website</a>.<p>

<A NAME="4"><b>What can family businesses do to protect themselves against family members (or their ex-spouses) trying to destroy the business?</b></A><BR>
(<A HREF="#contents">Back to Contents</A>)<p>

<b> Open and Frequent Communication: </B> Careful planning can prevent most family business problems. Most often the problem arises because people within the family have different expectations, and understandings. This is more of a communication problem, than a business one. Regular meetings in which each family member can share their viewpoint and concerns can often minimize such miscommunications. It is key that all members feel their input is welcome.<p>

<b> Clarify the Succession of Control of the Business Early:</b>  It is also key that they understand their role in the succession of the business. A disgruntled son or daughter may feel that they, not their sibling, should have received controlling interest in the business. This leads to family dissension and frequently to litigation. Even if the succession is upheld, the cost (both economically and emotionally) to the business may be exorbitant.<p>

Although inheritance rights are governed by state laws, and differ from state to state, generally offspring have no right to inherit from their parents. Rarely would a child be able to overturn a parent's specific bequest in this way. Unfortunately, the offspring may not be seeing things clearly, and acting purely out of emotion. It is much better to face this while all parties are still alive, letting people know where they stand, rather than learning this for the first time through a cold document reaching from the grave. Any estate planning documentation must work along with the shareholders agreement, and a qualified lawyer must consulted when they are prepared.<p>

<b>Documentation:</b>  Documenting the understandings also helps define the expectations of the parties. The agreements most helpful to family businesses generally are employment agreements for family member employees and shareholders agreements (assuming the business is incorporated, or the operating agreement, as to limited liability companies, or partnership agreements, as to partnerships) to define the inter-relationship of the shareholders, and their rights upon dissolution, withdrawal from the company, termination as an employee, as well as their death or disability. Protecting the family from the marital breakup of a family business owner requires either an agreement with the future spouse or with the other shareholders to buy out the ex-spouse in the event of a divorce.<p>

Employment agreements should be prepared in the same manner as for non-family employees, and deal as well with any ownership issues. Sometimes the use of the family name should be protected by way of a confidentiality agreement or non-competition provision in the
agreement. The provisions of the employment agreement should dovetail with the shareholders agreement. The shareholder agreement should deal with officer responsibilities, directors positions (if any), voting trusts, personal guarantee issues, transfers of shares, valuation of the business for buyouts, and methods of paying any proceeds in a buyout. Super-majority provisions, where all or a substantial majority of the shareholders must agree to an action are common. The issues are really the same as in most closely-held companies.<p>

Antenuptial agreements (pre-marital agreements) are essential for each family member who is getting married and is part of a family-owned business. The antenuptial agreements can waive the spouse's claims against ownership of the family business. Antenuptial agreements are governed by state law, and requirements differ from state to state. They should make sure to choose a knowledgeable lawyer with experience in both family business and antenuptial agreements in their state. These agreements can be tricky and a badly drafted one, that doesn't carefully comply with state law will often be thrown out by the courts. <p>

Unfortunately, antenuptial agreements have to be entered into before the marriage, and will not prevent problems from arising with family members who are already married, in the event of a member's divorce. In that case, shareholder agreements can deal with the issues which would arise in the event of a divorce of one of the family members owners. The shareholders agreement can calculate the value of any member's interests in the family business and the payout of something of equivalent value, rather than splitting up the member's share in the business upon divorce. Courts may not enforce the restrictions on dividing the stock as part of a divorce settlement, but it's worth the attempt.<p>

A good family business lawyer will recommend that all family business members have entered into these key agreements, to protect the other family members.<p>

<A NAME="5"><b>What is the single most important legal issue faced a family business?</b></A><BR>
(<A HREF="#contents">Back to Contents</A>)<p>

It's hard to isolate one legal issue, but I would have to choose estate planning. Without careful estate planning, the government can destroy a business in succession with "death taxes." If the business can survive the lost of the family business leader, and calm the many non-family employees and officers, it still has to face the financing of the estate taxes. Although the federal government allows installment payments on certain qualified estate taxes, the taxes can still be overwhelming. Proper advance planning can minimize the adverse effect of estate taxes. Trusts and family-limited-partnerships are the vehicles being used, along with others, to minimize the tax impact of a shareholder's death.<p>

Depending on the age of the family business leader, insurance may be a preferred mechanism for funding taxes. Disability insurance is recommended as well. Insurance can also be used to fund the buyout in the event of the death, disability or termination of a shareholder, pursuant to the shareholders agreement. Your insurance or financial planner should be consulted as to the cost of funding such provisions with insurance. <p>

<A NAME="6"><b>Are there consultants and advisors specializing in family business to help balance the competing roles or family member and business associate?</b></A><BR>
(<A HREF="#contents">Back to Contents</A>)<p>

The more information made available to family businesses the better. Luckily, in the last 10 years, recognizing the need for formalized training in this area, many leading educational institutions have set up programs for family business study and consulting. We have worked with the George Rothman Institute of Entrepreneurial Studies, at Fairleigh Dickenson University in New Jersey. Through them and centers like them, family businesses can learn how to deal with the problems which are unique to them.<p>

In addition, there are many family business counselors which, like a marriage counselor, helps the families juggle the often competing roles of family member and employee-officer. Sometimes family business bring in a turnaround business specialist or family-business outside manager to help manage the family business during transitions or difficult times. These counselors and business specialists can be sourced from the leading family-business institutes located around the country.<P>

<A NAME="7"><b>Are things improving for family businesses with all this information available to them?</b></A><BR>
(<A HREF="#contents">Back to Contents</A>)<p>

Apparently, things are improving rapidly. The 1995 Mass Mutual survey results disclose that family businesses are taking formal planning more seriously than ever. The survey indicates that the number of owners who report having formalized an intergenerational transition plan, to transfer the operation of the business from one generation to the next, has more than doubled since the first survey in 1993, from 21% to 44% of the number of businesses responding.<p>

We attribute this to two essential factors: better training of the family members and better lawyering among small firm practitioners. <p>

With increasing understanding of their uniqueness and the need to combine good general business skills into the business, many family business leaders are requiring their family members to work for outside businesses before entering the family business. This allows someone else to do the initial and often painful introductory training, and helps the family member understand the need for conducting the family business first as a business. With this and other trends towards outside training,  the business acumen and sophistication of the family members is increasing rapidly.<p>

As the family members are becoming more sophisticated, so are the lawyers who provide them with advice. The demographics of the small firm practitioner has changed. Smaller firms have always been the choice for most of the family-owned businesses in the United States. Because of recent downsizing among the larger firms, and many lawyers having chosen to practice in a small firm environment for their own family reasons, the small firm lawyer is evolving. We are bringing the skills and education we have received representing Fortune 100 companies and learned how to adapt the more important business factors to the family-business model. Better business training on the part of the family members and better lawyering on the part of the advisors combine to make family businesses more formidable every day.<p>

Even with the optimistic increase in the proportion of family businesses having formalizing their transition policies, allowing an orderly transfer of the business from one generation to the next, according to the Mass Mutual results 56% have no formalized transition plans.<p>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/stroke.gif" HEIGHT=15 WIDTH=547><BR>
