<H2><A HREF="macmillan.html"><IMG SRC="macmillan.gif" ALT=""Killing Time"" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER="0" VSPACE="5" HSPACE="5"></A>The O.J. Simpson Civil Case:<BR>Pre-Trial Depositions</H2>

<P><B>Note:</B> Some of these files are quite long (200k+) and may take a few minutes to load. If you prefer, you may download a compressed (zipped) version of the file to your hard drive. (You'll need an <A HREF="/download/utility/">unzipping utility</A> to decompress the file).</P>

<P>We have removed names, addresses and telephone numbers from some of these documents to protect the privacy of several private citizens who were mentioned in the deposition.</P>

<P><B>O.J. Simpson Deposition</B><BR>
(View the Deposition: <A HREF="oj01.html">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="oj02.html">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="oj03.html">Day 3</A> | <A HREF="oj04.html">Day 4</A> | <A HREF="oj05.html">Day 5</A> | <A HREF="oj06.html">Day 6</A> | <A HREF="oj07.html">Day 7</A> | <A HREF="oj08.html">Day 8</A> | <A HREF="oj09.html">Day 9</A>)<BR>
(Download Zip File: <A HREF="oj01.zip">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="oj02.zip">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="oj03.zip">Day 3</A> | <A HREF="oj04.zip">Day 4</A> | <A HREF="oj05.zip">Day 5</A> | <A HREF="oj06.zip">Day 6</A> | <A HREF="oj07.zip">Day 7</A> | <A HREF="oj08.zip">Day 8</A> | <A HREF="oj09.zip">Day 9</A>)<BR>
These are the transcripts of nine of the first ten days of O.J. Simpson's deposition in the civil lawsuit brought against him by the families of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald Goldman. (The tenth transcript, dealing with Simpson's finances, is sealed). This is the first time Simpson has answered questions under oath about his activities just before, during and after the murders.</P>

<P><B>Denise Brown Deposition</B><BR>
(<A HREF="denise.html">Veiw the Deposition</A>) -- (<A HREF="denise.zip">Download Zip File</A>)<BR>
O.J. Simpson offered his former wife $5000 to have sex with him in May, 1994, according to Denise Brown in her May 2, 1996 deposition. As she did on the witness stand in the criminal trial, Brown recounts her memories of her sister's troubled marriage. <I>Editor's Note: Three pages of this 287-page deposition are missing.</I></P>

<P><B>Robert Kardashian Deposition</B><BR>
(View the Deposition: <A HREF="kardash1.html">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="kardash2.html">Day 2</A>) -- 
(Download Zip File: <A HREF="kardash1.zip">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="kardash2.zip">Day 2</A>)<BR>
Robert Kardashian, who read O.J. Simpson's letter defending himself and thanking friends after the Bronco chase, refused to answer key questions. He said he has acted as one of Simpson's attorneys since 1970 and many of the conversations he has had with his friend are protected under attorney-client privilege.</P>

<P><B>Lawrence Schiller Deposition</B><BR>
(<A HREF="schiller.html">Veiw the Deposition</A>) -- (<A HREF="schiller.zip">Download Zip File</A>)<BR>
Writer, director and producer Lawrence Schiller visited O.J. Simpson 16 times at the Los Angeles County Jail in November and December of 1994. A former neighbor who once directed Simpson in a music video, Schiller gained access to Simpson as a possible material witness in the criminal trial. But those visits were primarily used to produce, "I Want to Tell You," a book in which Simpson answers letters from the public and proclaims his innocence. Royalties from the book, which received a $1 million advance, were paid to Simpson's legal defense fund. In this June 7, 1996 deposition, lawyers for the family of Ronald Goldman asked about the 30 hours of interviews recorded in producing the book.</P>

<P><B>Jason Simpson Deposition</B><BR>
(<A HREF="jason.html">View the Deposition</A>) -- (<A HREF="jason.zip">Download Zip File</A>)<BR>
Jason Simpson, O.J. Simpson's son from his first marriage, denied in this May 8, 1996 deposition that his father engaged in domestic violence. But at one point in the criminal trial, considering the prosecution's evidence, he recalled, "the thought crossed [his] mind" that his father might be responsible for Nicole Brown Simpson's death. Simpson said he never questioned his father about the murders. But he said he is confident that his father is innocent.</P>

<P><B>Marcus Allen Deposition</B><BR>
(<A HREF="allen.html">View the Deposition</A>) -- (<A HREF="allen.zip">Download Zip File</A>)<BR>
Football star Marcus Allen recounted his jailhouse conversations with O.J. Simpson and denied that he had a romantic relationship with Nicole Brown Simpson in this May, 31 1996 deposition.</P>

<P><B>Kim Goldman Deposition</B><BR>
(<A HREF="kgoldman.html">View the Deposition</A>) -- 
(<A HREF="kgoldman.zip">Download Zip File</A>)<BR>
Kimberly Goldman described her brother, Ronald, as having played a central role in raising her, in this Feb. 5, 1996 deposition. After her parents split up, he helped take care of her when her father was at work. Defense lawyers probed Goldman for her family's motivations in bringing wrongful death charges against O.J. Simpson. Goldman said she was shocked that her mother filed a suit because Ronald hadn't seen the woman in more than 15 years before his death.</P>

<P><B>Fred Goldman Deposition</B><BR>
(<A HREF="fgoldman.html">View the Deposition</A>) -- 
(<A HREF="fgoldman.zip">Download Zip File</A>)<BR>
Fredric Goldman recounted his relationship with his son Ronald and events leading up to his decision to sue O.J. Simpson in civil court for Ronald's death. This deposition was given on February 9, 1996.</p>

<P><B>Al Cowlings Deposition</B><BR>
(View the Deposition: <A HREF="cowl1.html">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="cowl2.html">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="cowl3.html">Day 3</A> | <A HREF="cowl4.html">Day 4</A>)<BR>
(Download Zip File: <A HREF="cowl1.zip">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="cowl2.zip">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="cowl3.zip">Day 3</A>| <A HREF="cowl4.zip">Day 4</A>)<BR>
Allen Cowlings, O.J. Simpson's longtime friend, asserted his Fifth Amendment privilege against self-incrimination throughout his deposition, taken April 16, 17 & 26, and May 15, 1996. "Why don't you just give me immunity, and I can answer these questions for you," Cowlings told the plaintiffs' lawyers. Two months later, Judge Alan Haber denied granting Cowlings limited immunity against prosecution. Cowlings finished his deposition on May 15. Judge Haber's ruling means that Cowlings does not have to answer further questions in a deposition.</P>

<P><B>Christian Reichardt Deposition</B><BR>
(View the Deposition: <A HREF="reich1.html">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="reich2.html">Day 2</A>) -- 
(Download Zip File: <A HREF="reich1.zip">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="reich2.zip">Day 2</A>)<BR>
Christian Reichardt, O.J. Simpson's friend and Faye Resnick's former boyfriend, testified in the criminal trial that Simpson was relaxed and happy the day before the murders and grieving afterwards. These are the transcripts of his deposition, taken on March 22 & 25, 1996.</P>

<P><B>Cora Fischman Deposition</B><BR>
(View the Deposition: <A HREF="fischm1.html">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="fischm2.html">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="fischm3.html">Day 3</A>) -- 
(Download Zip File: <A HREF="fischm1.zip">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="fischm2.zip">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="fischm3.zip">Day 3</A>)<BR>
Cora Fischman, a friend of the Simpsons, claimed she was unaware of most of the abuse Nicole Brown Simpson said she suffered in her diary. Fischman said that at the time of her death, Nicole was leading a "dangerous life" that involved drugs. Fischman claimed that Nicole's friends threatened to ostracize her if she did not say that O.J. was responsible for Nicole's murder.</P>

<P><B>Kato Kaelin Deposition</B><BR>
(View the Deposition: <A HREF="kato1.html">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="kato2.html">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="kato3.html">Day 3</A>) -- 
(Download Zip File: <A HREF="kato1.zip">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="kato2.zip">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="kato3.zip">Day 3</A>)<BR>
In his three-day deposition, taken February 14, 15 & 20, 1996, Brian "Kato" Kaelin talked about his relationship with O.J. Simpson and Nicole Brown Simpson, the couple's violent relationship, and events leading up to the murders. Simpson was angry with his former wife for "playing hardball" with him in granting access to their children, Kato recalled, and was in an extremely bad mood shortly before his former wife and Ronald Goldman were murdered. When Simpson and Kaelin went to McDonald's that evening, the conversation was so strained that he felt awkward about asking Simpson for a straw, Kaelin said.</P>

<P><B>Faye Resnick Deposition</B><BR>
(View the Deposition: <A HREF="resnick1.html">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="resnick2.html">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="resnick3.html">Day 3</A>) -- 
(Download Zip File: <A HREF="resnick1.zip">Day 1</A> | <A HREF="resnick2.zip">Day 2</A> | <A HREF="resnick3.zip">Day 3</A>)<BR>
From physical beatings to psychological torture, O.J. Simpson was obsessed with controlling his former wife, according to Faye Resnick in her deposition, taken February 10-12, 1996. Along with death threats, Simpson terrorized her by reporting her to the IRS, she said. She describes O.J. Simpson as a drug-abusing wife beater, playing the part of star athlete in public. But when he got angry with his wife, "His jaw would protrude, his teeth would clench, sweat would come pouring from his head," she said. "The only way to describe it is animalistic."</P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P><A HREF="/discuss/gateway.html"><B>Talk Back!</B></A><BR>
What do you think will happen in the civil suit against O.J. Simpson? What's the best part of these depositions? Talk to other Simpson-watchers in our new <A HREF="/discuss/gateway.html">discussion group</a>. If you don't have a password for our discussion area, you can <A HREF=/register/>register now</a>.</P>

