<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: Oklahoma City Bombing</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/top-casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/top-casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>

<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<H2>The Oklahoma City Bombing Case</H2>



<P><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/casefiles/mcveigh.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=5

VSPACE=0 BORDER=0><P><B>Update:</B>Documents unsealed Jan. 3 indicate a witness could tie Timothy McVeigh <I>(Shown to the left)</I> to phone calls made to Terry Nichols shortly before the 1995 bombing of the Oklahoma City federal building.</P>

<P>The statements by Thomas Manning, a tire dealer from Junction City, Kan., were among several documents released to the public.</P>

<p>Manning is said to have sold McVeigh the 1977 Mercury Marquis that was allegedly used as the getaway car after the April 19, 1995 bombing. Four days before the blast, McVeigh allegedly left Manning's Firestone dealership and called Nichols and a Ryder rental truck agency.</P>

<P>The government claims the Ryder truck McVeigh rented was used to carry the bomb he and Nichols built that killed 168 people and injured more than 500 others.</P>

<P>U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch set March 31 as the trial date for McVeigh. Nichols' trial date has yet to be set. The defendants could face the death penalty if convicted of federal conspiracy and murder charges. </P>
</P>

<P><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="documents/">Transcripts and Court

Documents</A></FONT SIZE=+2><BR>

The indictments, FBI affidavits and more.</P>



<P><FONT SIZE=+1><A

HREF="/discuss/gateway.html">Discuss the Case</A></FONT SIZE=+2><BR>

<A HREF="/register/">Register</A> for our message boards and trade your insights and opinions with other trial watchers.</P>



<H3><B>Reports from Court TV and American Lawyer Media</B></H3>



<UL TYPE=DISC>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/septrial2.html">Bombing Trial's New Look, Issues</a><br>

One of the biggest federal trials ever staged suddenly has been transformed into two of the biggest trials ever. And as the Oklahoma City bombing case moves forward, that transformation not only has implications for each side's legal strategy, but also will touch witnesses, the crime victims and their families, and U.S. taxpayers. </P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/blitz.html">No Media Blitz for McVeigh</A><BR>

Accused Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh will not be going on a media blitz before his trial. An Oct. 4 ruling denies McVeigh's motion to be allowed to conduct a series of interviews with hand-picked television and print reporters. </P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/septrial.html">Bomb Defendants Want Separate Trials Severance Payoff</A><BR>

With the start of the Oklahoma City bombing trial still months away, prosecutors are facing their most serious challenge to date as they try to fend off the defendants' push for separate trials. </P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/okla918.html">Monsters and Boy Scouts</A><BR>

At first blush, accused Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh's pending motion for permission to give media interviews -- including one with a famous TV journalist, to be chosen from a gaggle of eager applicants who have already auditioned for the opportunity -- might seem an occasion for revulsion. But, says Stuart Taylor Jr., the motion should be granted.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/media.html">McVeigh's Media Bid Tests Inmate Rights</A><BR>

Accused Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh's bid to conduct interviews with a number of hand-picked national reporters is more than just a media strategy--it also raises provocative legal questions about jailed defendants, the First Amendment rights of pretrial detainees, and the role of the press in the trial process.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/okla94b.html">Joseph Hartzler: Low Key, High Pressure</A><BR>

The top prosecutor in the Oklahoma City bombing case plays a surprisingly quiet role as leader of the DOJ's <A HREF="reports/okla94a.html">'Dream Team'</A>.</P>

<LI><P><A HREF="reports/tigar.html">Nichols' Lawyer: A Tigar's Stripes</A><BR>

Michael Tigar, in an interview after winning an acquittal for Maj. Debra Meeks on charges of sodomy and conduct unbecoming an officer, says he had in mind his representation of one of the men charged with blowing up the Oklahoma City federal building. But he also could have been remembering his early career, when he successfully challenged the Selective Service for putting Vietnam War protesters at the top of its induction lists.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/troubling.html">More Power to the

Bureau?</A><BR>

Testimony about police behavior in the Oklahoma City case has troubled

many civil libertarians, scholars, and defense lawyers, who warn that

if the FBI played it too close to the line in the Oklahoma City probe,

this may be a taste of things to come.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/fine.html">Fine-Tuning TV Coverage</A><BR>

In permitting a closed-circuit broadcast of the Oklahoma City bombing

trial, Chief U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch managed both to

satisfy a congressional mandate that the trial be televised and to

address defense attorneys' vocal concerns for their clients' right to a fair trial.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/redraw.html">Bombing Case Lawyer Redraws Map</A><BR>

Look in any road atlas, and you'll find that Denver is 609 miles from Oklahoma City. But don't tell that to defense lawyer Michael Tigar, who managed to shave more than 300 miles off that distance in a recent court filing in the Oklahoma City bombing case.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/rethink.html">Rethinking the 5th Amendment</A><BR>

If Timothy McVeigh fails to take the stand at trial, the prosecutor will be barred from commenting on his silence, and the jury will be told not to infer anything from his silence. Is it time to reassess the 5th Amendment?</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/nra.html">The NRA Under the Gun</A><BR>

The bombing accentuated the National Rifle Association's common ground with militias. Should this powerful lobbying group soften its rhetoric?</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/siege.html">FBI's New Siege Mentality</A><BR>

Welcome to the Critical Incident Response Group. In the wake of the bombings at the World Trade Center and Oklahoma City, this unit is helping the U.S. fight terrorism on its own soil.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/represent.html">Representing the Accused Bomber</A><BR>

Defense lawyer Stephen Jones, who is representing bombing suspect Timothy McVeigh and has defended controversial people like Abbie Hoffman, says that declining the Oklahoma case would be like "living a lie."</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/toiling.html">Toiling in the Rubble</A><BR>

Federal prosecutors accustomed to assembling their cases in antiseptic offices scrambled to begin a massive investigation in a dank, two-story warehouse whose windows were shattered by the blast.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/scramble.html">Scrambling to Find a Defender</A><BR>

Timothy McVeigh's first appointed lawyers labored under a sharp conflict of interest that cast serious doubt on whether they could defend McVeigh: Both had lost friends in the bombing.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/nlawyers.html">Nichols' Lawyers: The Odd

Couple</A><BR>

Michael Tigar, a leftist law professor, and Ronald Woods, a conservative career prosecutor, are an odd yet formidable defense team for bombing suspect Terry Nichols.</P>



<LI><P><A HREF="reports/tigar.html">From the Pen of Michael Tigar</A><BR>

The following is an excerpt from "Defendant's Rights vs. Press" (Austin American-Statesman, Oct. 4, 1987) by Terry Nichols's lawyer Michael Tigar.</P>

</UL>



<P><A HREF="http://pathfinder.com/pathfinder/features/okc/"><B>Oklahoma Reports from <I>Time Online</I></B></A><BR>

Time Magazine's online coverage includes an exclusive interview with Timothy McVeigh and a photo essay on some of the victims.</P>



