<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV News: Garcia v. Garcia</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<h2>Garcia v. Garcia</h2>
Daily Developments Dec. 11 -- Jan 6<HR>
<P><B>December 11</B><BR>
The Grateful Dead's leader, Jerry Garcia, earned fame and fortune as a musician and clothes designer. But years of drug use, combined with his failing health and bad legal advice, made him unfit to enter into a divorce settlement with his second wife, according to his estate's lawyer, Paul Camera.</P>

<P>But David Phillips, attorney for Carolyn Adams Garcia, Jerry's second wife, claimed that the estate is merely reneging on a legitimate community property settlement.</P>

<P>At the center of this dispute is a 13-line, one-paragraph agreement that Carolyn Adams Garcia said she drafted herself, in which Jerry agreed to pay her $5 million.</P>

<P> Phillips said the agreement is a valid contract, in which Carolyn accepted the payment in exchange for her right, following a 12-year marriage, to an equal division of the couple's community property. But Camera said it was merely a memorandum that was to lead to a formalized settlement that was never reached.</P>

<P>The burden of proof is on Carolyn Adams Garcia to prove the settlement was fair. The estate's burden is to prove the agreement isn't enforceable.</P>

<P><B>Respondent's Opening Statement</B><BR>
Phillips said Jerry Garcia signed an agreement to pay his client $5 million over 20 years, at not less than $250,000 a year. The couple reached this agreement without the assistance of their divorce attorneys and it came about at Garcia's request, he said.</P>

<P>When Garcia filed for divorce in 1990, he agreed to temporary monthly payments of $24,000, and these payments continued until the divorce agreement went into effect in January 1994. At that time, the payments were reduced to about $20,000 a month ($250,000 divided by 12 months), as called for in the settlement agreement. As no time did anyone in Garcia's legal camp object to the payments, which continued until the singer's death in August 1995, Phillips said. </P>

<P>At the time of Garcia's death, he had made 18 payments of $20, 883, apparently in keeping with the terms of the alleged contract, Phillips said.</P>

<P><B>Petitioner's Opening Statement</B><BR>
Garcia was a unique person, an artist who wasn't too concerned with money, Camera said. Garcia was also a product of the drug culture that he so frequently sang about. Years of drug use left him suffering from "hyper-suggestibility," meaning he was an easy mark for his second wife and his lawyer David Hellman, Camera said, suggesting a conspiracy.</P>

<P>Camera said Garcia was addicted to heroin, cocaine, LSD and other drugs. Though he would not go so far as to say Garcia was incompetent when he signed the agreement in 1993, he charged Adams Garcia with being a manipulative opportunist who "bullied" her ex-husband.</P>

<P>In addition to questioning the validity of the couple's divorce settlement, the estate also questioned whether Jerry and Carolyn Adams Garcia were legally wed. Camera claimed that the two agreed to marry merely to give Jerry a tax advantage.</P>

<P>If Adams Garcia was able to take advantage of her husband, it was because she had the help of David Hellman, Garcia's own attorney, Camera said. Hellman, who represented Garcia as an accountant and personal attorney, was a co-executor of Garcia's will. Yet Camera claimed Hellman, who represented Adams Garcia in several matters, had a conflict of interest. </P>

<P><B>December 12</B><BR>
Defendant Carolyn Adams Garcia read to the court a love letter from her late husband to undercut claims that her marriage to Jerry Garcia was a sham.</P>

<P>"You tickle me with your sweet talk. I build up a vision of you on the bed and watch you form the words," Adams Garcia said on the witness stand, reading from the letter, which was printed on hotel stationery, apparently written when Garcia was on tour with his band, the Grateful Dead, in Chicago.</P>

<P>"I sink into you. I worship you . I love you on every level, every way," the letter concludes. It is signed, "Your devoted ugly Jer." </P>

<P>Aside from this emotional moment, most of Adams Garcia's testimony was devoted to describing the community property from her marriage and the alleged settlement agreement between the couple.</P>

<P>As the Grateful Dead's popularity rocketed, so did Garcia's income. He and his wife's joint tax returns from 1981 to 1990 showed their income increased from about $200,000 to more than $2 million a year. Adams Garcia testified that she and her husband had holdings in business, art and music ventures and shared joint bank accounts. Though they lived apart for long stretches, she said she and her husband were devoted to each other. </P>

<P>The witness recounted her on again, off again relationship with Garcia, from when they first lived together in 1967, through their first break-up in 1975 and 1981 marriage. </P>

<P>After the 1975 split, Garcia gave his then-girlfriend the Stinson Beach, Calif. house they lived in with their two children. She and the children later moved to Oregon.</P>

<P>The couple reunited briefly in 1977, when Garcia was supposedly ``hiding out'' after a fight with Deborah Koons -- who later became his third wife and widow. In 1980, while Adams Garcia was attending college in Massachusetts, she and Garcia began spending more time together. Each time his two bands -- the Jerry Garcia Band and the Grateful Dead -- passed through the state, she joined the tours. In Christmas of 1981, Jerry and Carolyn Adams Garcia and their children formed a household again. They married on Dec. 31, 1981, backstage at the Oakland Coliseum Arena after a concert. </P>

<P>Though Adams Garcia testified that she and Jerry intended to buy a house together in Marin County in the spring of 1982, his difficulties with the IRS led him to decide to hold off. As the tax trouble dragged on, she said she returned to Oregon to allow her daughters to return to school there.</P>

<P>It wasn't until Jerry Garcia fell into a diabetic coma in 1986 that his wife returned to the Bay Area. She remained with him after he recovered. About that time, she became a half-owner of a new company, Consensus Reality Inc., formed to handled his business deals outside the Grateful Dead. </P>

<P>The Garcias separated again in January of 1990, and Jerry agreed to pay Carolyn temporary family support of $24,000 a month until they could reach a settlement. But by the spring of 1993, with no property settlement in sight, Garcia Adams testified that her husband called her, frustrated with the slow pace of the divorce, and asked for a face-to-face meeting. When Adams drafted the $5 million agreement, allegedly at her husband's request, she said her goal was for a simple, honest settlement that would resolve all issues.</P>

<P>On cross-examination, estate attorney Paul Camera tried to point out that the alleged contract's lacked "consideration" -- a legal term for a fair exchange between parties -- and therefore wasn't enforceable. He asked the witness to explain what Jerry Garcia received as a trade-off for the promise to pay $5 million over 20 years. Freedom from her asking for money, she said.</P>

<P>Camera also attacked the alleged contract for its vagueness. He questioned the witness on whether the monthly family support payments of $24,000 was to stop when the agreement went into force. The witness said that that was her "assumption," though it is not specified in the agreement. Camera said the contract also did not mention how the agreement would effect overdue family support. </P>

<P>When Camera pointed out other apparent weaknesses in the agreement, Adams simply replied, ``I tried.''</P>

<P><B>December 13</B><BR>
David Hellman, the lawyer that allegedly betrayed Jerry Garcia, was called as the estate's first witness.</P>

<P>Estate lawyer Paul Camera asked that Hellman be declared a hostile witness. But the judge denied that motion.</P>

<P>Hellman agreed that he could be considered Garcia's ``general counsel.'' Starting in 1974, Hellman handled a variety of legal and accounting work for the rock star. From 1992 to 1995, Garcia granted Hellman power of attorney.</P>

<P>Suggesting that Hellman might have taken advantage of Garcia, Camera asked about the band leader's ``bad drug years.'' Hellman denied the possibility that he exploited his client. `He was lucid and intelligent,'' Hellman said, claiming that Garcia never came into his office high on drugs.</P>

<P>But Hellman admitted that he was closely involved in his client's personal life. When Jerry Garcia and Carolyn Adams split-up in 1975, after living together for eight years and having two children together, Hellman drafted the agreement in which Adams was given the couple's house in Stinson Beach, Calif., and all its contents, in exchange for no future demand for money. </P>

<P>Camera tried to show the court there was no legal reason for such an agreement. Adams, merely a girlfriend at the time, had no legal claim on any of the property. This settlement was made before the landmark Lee Marvin case in which a live-in partner was granted alimony for the first time. Hellman said he drafted the agreement based on what he was told by Garcia and Garcia's manager.</P>

<P>Hellman flatly denied ever saying that Jerry and Carolyn Adams Garcia married in 1981 purely to ease Garcia's tax problems.</P>

<P>In questioning Hellman about the couple's 1993 settlement agreement, Camera tried to show that Hellman was closely involved in aiding Adams Garcia. Hellman held fast, however, that he simply offered his office to the couple for a meeting, and that he told both that he was not acting as counsel. He said he told both of them to consult divorce attorneys. But Hellman conceded he was present for the entire first meeting in which Jerry asked Carolyn to come up with a proposal of what she wanted in a settlement. </P>

<P>Suggesting that Garcia was eventually unhappy with the settlement and loosing faith in Hellman, Camera pointed out that  Garcia withheld Hellman's power of attorney in 1995 and asked about the possibility of getting the agreement declared null and void.</P>

<P><B>December 16-17</B><BR>
No court.</P>

<P><B>December 18</B><BR>
The estate continued questioning lawyer David Hellman, Jerry Garcia's personal attorney, attempting to show that he had a conflict of interest, resulting in Garcia receiving inadequate legal advice.</P>

<P><B>According to Hellman:</B></P>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI><P>Consensus Reality Inc. -- an entity set up in 1986 to issue salary and pay withholding tax on Garcia's non-income outside of the Grateful Dead  --  was formed with Garcia and Carolyn Adams Garcia as co-owners. Estate lawyer Paul Camera asked Hellman if he advised Jerry he was giving up a significant amount of money to Carolyn, sparking an objection from Phillips. Hellman said he didn't think of it because the two were married. Camera suggested that this move was another example of Hellman favoring Carolyn at Jerry's expense. </P>

<LI><P>Hellman admitted that he inflated values in financial statements he prepared for the couple in conjunction with their application to buy real estate. </P>

<LI><P>Hellman testified that most of Jerry's income earning entities --his company interests and the bands -- were formed before his 1981 marriage to Adams.</P>

<LI><P>He met with Adams Garcia in the early 1980s several times regarding drafts of wills that were never signed. </P>
</UL>

<P><B>December 19</B><BR>
Estate lawyer Paul Camera hammered home his theme that Jerry Garcia's lawyer David Hellman abandoned -- and perhaps conspired against -- the famous guitarist.</P>

<P>Focusing on the May 11, 1993 meeting between Garcia and Carolyn Adams Garcia, in which the $5 million agreement was signed, Camera asked Hellman if he even considered whether Garcia could make the $250,000 a year payments.</P>

<P>Hellman admitted that he reviewed the agreement. But everything happened so quickly, he didn't have time to consider the issue.  He said he didn't advise Garcia to hold off signing it because it wasn't his role. He maintained that he wasn't a divorce lawyer for either party. Both Jerry and Carolyn had divorce lawyers and he assumed they were talking to them.</P>

<P><B>Other highlights:</B></P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI><P>Hellman had frequent one-on-one meetings with Adams Garcia when Garcia wasn't present.</P>

	<LI><P>Hellman didn't advise Jerry Garcia against giving his wife half ownership of Consensus Reality Inc., which brought in income from assets acquired before the couple wed.</P>

	<LI><P>Even though Garcia had legal counsel, he mistakenly believed he had to sign a property settlement before he could remarry.</P>
</UL>


<P><B>December 20</B><BR>
A forensic accounting expert testified that Jerry and Carolyn Adams Garcia's community property hardly justified the $5 million settlement agreement.</P>

<P>Richard Schiller, an expert witness for the estate, valued the couple's community property at $2.1 million. Of that total, Schiller said Adams was due $1.61 million. Considering Adams received bank account funds of $276,000, autos valued at $82,000, and a house valued at $194,000, Carolyn was due $507,000, he said.</P>

<P>Considering that Carolyn has already received $375,00 over 18 payments under the 1993 settlement agreement, Schiller said that Adams received most of what she was due.</P>

<P>On cross examination, Defense lawyer David Phillips pointed out that Schiller did not consider the Grateful Dead's catalog of songs and other assets when making his estimates.</P>


<P><B>December 23</B><BR>
Deborah Koons Garcia testified that her late husband told her early in her relationship that he made "three big mistakes in the last 15 years." Those were: becoming a drug addict, marrying Carolyn Garcia to save on his taxes, and getting involved with Manasha Matheson, the mother of his youngest daughter, nine-year-old Keelin.</P>

<P>The widow, who cut off the $20,883-a-month payments to Carolyn Adams Garcia after the band leader's death, testified that Jerry and Carolyn Adams Garcia's marriage was a sham and that Jerry was trying to revoke the couple's $5 million divorce settlement shortly before his fatal heart attack.</P>

<P>Koons Garcia, 47, described meeting Garcia in 1973 in Long Island, New York, while hitching a ride with the Grateful Dead after a show.  She says they began a correspondence that continued while she traveled in Europe through 1974.  A year later, they moved in together. </P>

<P>They reached a "rocky place" in 1977 and parted. At a chance encounter at a health food store 15 years later, they met again and rekindled their relationship.</P>

<P>Koons Garcia testified that Garcia continued to court her, but she insisted he finalize his divorce from his second wife.  She said that Garcia came to her after working out the $5 million dollar settlement, telling her that his marriage was a sham, a joke that would cost him a fortune. </P>

<P>The witness said although Garcia was upset with the $5 million deal, he mostly cared about marrying her and about moving on with his life. Garcia, she said, had been advised that taking the matter to court would be more costly because of the legal fees,. A few weeks before his death, she recalled him saying the agreement was "unfair" and he began to inquire what his legal options were.</P>

<P>Koons Garcia's testimony is scheduled to continue Thursday. Because of the Christmas holiday, there is no court  scheduled for Tuesday and Wednesday.</P>

<P><B>December 24 - 25</B><BR>
No court.</P>

<P><B>December 26</B><BR>
Carolyn Adams Garcia insisted that she did not meet her late ex-husband's lawyer until after her marriage. But a will drafted about a year before she married Jerry Garcia suggested otherwise.</P>

<P>Paul Camara, lawyer for the estate, used his cross-examination of  Adams Garcia to advance the estate's theory that Jerry Garcia was betrayed by his own lawyer, David Hellman, upon entering a $5 million divorce settlement </P>

<P>But even when confronted  with the will, which Hellman drafted in 1980, Adams Garcia maintained that did not recall meeting Hellman until later. </P>

<P>In a heated exchange, Camera argued that Adams Garcia and Hellman colluded to force Jerry into a "sham" marriage, valid only because of "legal mumbo jumbo." </P>

<P>But Adams Garcia testified that she pushed Garcia to marry because it was "an embarrassment" to have children by two different men while married to another. Pressed to reveal who initiated the marriage, she testified that in the cavalier crowd Garcia associated with, it took some prodding to get him to agree to married life. "That's the way it was in the seventies" she said. "That's the way it was in a rock and roll band."</P>

<P>Earlier in the day, Deborah Koons Garcia finished her testimony, defending her decisions as executrix of her late husband's estate. Under the cross examination of attorney David Phillips, she admitted that in 1994 and 1995, her husband paid for all of her expenses, except her two house mortgages. Despite an annual income of more than $300,000, she testified that she received $22,000 a month in support from her spouse. </P>

<P>Phillips also established that in an April 25, 1996 petition to the court for an $18,000 monthly allowance, Deborah stated that the estate was solvent. The next day, she informed the court that the estate may be insolvent in response to Adams Garcia's petition for attorney's fees. </P>

<P>To suggest that Koons Garcia might have tailored her testimony to fit her case, Phillips read from her deposition to show that there was no mention of Garcia calling his marriage to second wife a sham and a joke when he initially told her about the $5 million deal, an apparent contradiction to her trial testimony.</P>

<P><B>December 27</B><BR>
Former Grateful Dead bassist Phil Lesh testified that he rarely saw defendant Carolyn Adams Garcia on the band's tours after her marriage to Jerry Garcia.</P>

<P>The estate called Lesh to prove that Jerry Garcia was involved in a loveless marriage and may have been bullied by his second wife.</P>

<P>But Lesh, a founding member of the Grateful Dead, conceded that more than 30 years were "one big, smoky haze" and he couldn't exactly remember when the defendant was with the band. But he recalled that she was at shows or on the band's chartered plane "very infrequently, if at all" in the 1980s.</P>

<P>Attorneys for Jerry Garcia's estate contend Jerry and Carolyn Adams Garcia married in 1981 only to save on taxes and that she coerced her drug-fogged husband into agreeing to the settlement in 1993.</P>

<P>Lesh's testimony contradicted previous assertions by Carolyn Adams Garcia that she had gone on parts of at least two tours a year in the 1980s." </P>

<P>Lesh said, "Jerry and I never really talked about his private life." But he described Garcia as a "cool dude . . . a very lovable guy and an excellent musician, full of life, full of humor."</P>

<P>Lesh said Garcia had never said anything to him about his impending marriage to Carolyn Garcia.
But he described her as "forthcoming, aggressive." When asked whether she was a bully, he said, "I'm familiar with that component of her personality."</P>

<P>But he added, "None of Jerry's women had exactly been shrinking violets."</P>

<P>Earlier in the day, Carolyn Adams Garcia testified that she attended many Grateful Dead shows in the 1980s. Though she did not give a specific numbers, she said she probably attended more shows in the 1960s and 1970s. Her testimony was interrupted to allow Lesh to take the stand.</P>

<P><B>December 30</B><BR>
Jerry Garcia's bookkeeper testified that she thought her deceased boss married his second wife for tax purposes.</P>

<P>Suzanne Stephens' testimony supported the estate's position that Jerry Garcia's second marriage was simply one of convenience. </P>

<P>But under cross-examination, Carolyn Garcia's lawyer, David Phillips, suggested that Stephens' may have been pressured by the estate, who is her current employer. Stephens said that on May 8, 1996 -- with barely an hour's notice -- she was asked to sign a statement in the presence of estate lawyer Paul Camera and executor Deborah Koons Garcia. In the statement, Stephens declares that Jerry Garcia's personal attorney, David Hellman, told her that Jerry and Carolyn Garcia were getting married for tax reasons.</P>

<P>Other Testimony:</P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI><B>Jack Phillips</B>, an accountant, testified about the potential value of Garcia's estate. Phillips said that his company, which compiled the data used by the estate's forensic accountant, did not value the catalog of Grateful Dead and Jerry Garcia Songs, nor did it put a value on master recordings of live Grateful Dead performances. Defense lawyer David Phillips is trying to show that the estate deliberately overlooked these assets.

	<LI><B>Max Gutierrez</B>, lawyer for Deborah Koons Garcia, testified that Hellman claimed to have not attended the meeting when Jerry and Carolyn Garcia signed the $5 million divorce settlement. Hellman and Carolyn Adams have subsequently testified that Hellman was present when the deal was signed. The estate wants to show that Hellman was trying to hide his involvement in the deal.
</UL>
<P><B>January 2</B><BR>
A Grateful Dead roadie testified that Jerry Garcia married his second wife, at least in part, to reduce his taxes.</P>

<P>Steve Parish, who began working for the Grateful Dead as a security guard in 1970, testified that Garcia told him, "I love Mountain Girl [Carolyn Garcia] and I've got to straighten out my taxes."</P>

<P>Parish was the only witness, besides Deborah Koons Garcia, to quote Jerry Garcia as saying that the marriage was for tax purposes. But Parish insisted that Garcia never said that he only married Carolyn for the tax break. </P>

<P>Parish also testified that he did not recall seeing Carolyn Garcia at Grateful Dead performances in the 1980s; although he did see her at the hometown performances.</P>

<P>A reluctant witness for the estate, Parish considers himself a friend of both Garcia's widow and Garcia's second wife. At 17, he began traveling with the band. Over the next 25 years he served as security guard, guitar technician, manager of the Jerry Garcia Band, and stage manager for the Grateful Dead. He was Garcia's best man when he married Deborah Koons. Parish testified that he has refused money to talk about Garcia and at one point he was willing to go to jail rather than testify in this "unseemly case."</P>

<P>At points, Paul Camera, lawyer for the estate, seemed exasperated with his witness, as testimony that appeared to hurt his case went on the record. Parish explained that when he told Camera that Carolyn and Jerry Garcia were not together as man and wife from 1979 to 1986, he meant that they did not have a typical "Ozzie and Harriet" marriage. "We were the Dead, we did things differently," he testified. </P>

<P>On cross-examination, Parish testified that life on the road was not family oriented. He reiterated Carolyn Garcia's testimony that a macho atmosphere -- which sometimes involved members of Hell's Angels pervaded the Dead -- making it more difficult for a mother of young children to tour with the band. </P>

<P>Upon the completion of Parish's testimony, Camera announced that he would like to call himself as a witness, possibly to counter some of Parish's statements about their conversations and to testify that David Hellman, Jerry Garcia's personal attorney, said in August 1995 that he was not present when the May 11, 1993 agreement was signed. </P>

<P><B>Other Highlights:</B></P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI><P><B>Stilson Letter:</B> Camera read into the record portions of Deborah Koons Garcia's deposition in which she said Jerry Garcia was upset over the May 11, 1993 agreement. In the deposition, Deborah Koons Garcia also testified that her deceased husband told her the marriage to Carolyn Garcia was a sham and that he signed the agreement so he could divorce and move on with his life. Camera attempted to introduce a letter Jerry Garcia's deceased family law attorney, Bruce Stilson, wrote to a consultant, quoting Garcia as saying that his second marriage was for legal and tax conveniences. Carolyn Garcia's lawyer, David Phillips, objected, calling the letter "double hearsay." The judge sustained his objection. </P>

	<LI><P><B>Estate Value:</B> Forensic accountant, Victor Levi, testified that Carolyn Adams is entitled to $4.5 million, in direct contradiction to the $1.3 million estimate by Richard Schiller, the estate's expert. Levi valued the estate at the time of the May 11, 1993 settlement agreement. Schiller valued it at the time of the January 6, 1990 separation. Levi estimated unreleased audio and video recordings at $4.6 million. Schiller gave these recordings no value, claiming that because the Grateful Dead allowed concert attendees to record the band's performances, the market demand for unreleased live recordings is greatly diminished.</P>

	<LI><P><B>What's Ahead:</B> The cross-examination of Levi will continue. Paul Camera is then expected to call himself and his forensic accountant Richard Schiller. Once testimony is complete, there will be a half hour break before closing arguments.</P>
</UL>

<P><B>January 3</B><BR>
Forensic accountants battled over the value of Jerry Garcia's estate as testimony drew to a close.</P>

<P>Estate accountant Richard Schiller testified that Carolyn Garcia is entitled to approximately $1.3 million Carolyn Garcia's expert, Victor Levi, countered that she is entitled to approximately $4.5 million. </P>

<P>The principal reason  for the different estimates is that Schiller determined the value of the estate as of Jan 6, 1990, the date of separation between Jerry and Carolyn Garcia. Levi used the value of the estate as of May 11, 1993, the date of the $5 million agreement. Garcia earned approximately $7 million dollars between Schiller's date and Levi's date. </P>

<P>Another reason why Levi's estimate was greater: He estimated that unreleased audio and video recordings are worth $4.6 million and that copyrights are worth $1.9 million. Schiller assigned no value to these items. </P>

<P>The judge does not need to determine the exact value of the Garcia estate. He only needs a measure to determine whether the $5 million settlement between the Garcias was equitable and that Jerry Garcia could have afforded to pay it. If Carolyn Garcia loses this trial, there will be another trial to determine the actual value of the estate and what her share should be. </P>

<P>The remainder of the afternoon was spent entering exhibits. Objections once again were raised to Deborah Koons Garcia's testimony that Jerry Garcia allegedly told her that his second marriage was a sham and that he thought the $5 million settlement agreement was a rip-off. Carolyn Garcia's lawyer argued that this testimony is not reliable because Deborah Koons Garcia had to much at stake in this case. The judge deferred a ruling until Monday, but said he is inclined to overrule the motion.</P>

<P><B>What's Next:</B> Closing arguments are scheduled for Monday. When the lawyers are finished, the judge will take the matter under submission. He has 90 days to release a written ruling.</P>

<P><B>January 6</B><BR>
After heated accusations in closing arguments, the judge took the case under submission and said he expects to release a ruling in about 10 days. He has ninety days to release a ruling.</P>

<P>Carolyn Garcia's attorney David Phillips suggested that a special place in accountants' hell be reserved for the estate's accountant for failing to value Jerry Garcia's songs catalog and vault of unreleased music. Estate attorney Paul Camera attacked Carolyn Garcia's credibility and compared Jerry Garcia's personal attorney, David Hellman, to Richard Nixon. </P>

<P>In the morning, Phillips argued that Jerry Garcia signed the May 11, 1993 agreement freely, voluntarily and with full knowledge of the facts. The agreement was intended to resolve any outstanding properties between Carolyn and Jerry Garcia, specifically earnings from his musical endeavors. The validity of the contract in Carolyn Garcia's mind was evident in the fact that she made no further efforts to obtain full disclosure of her husband's estate, nor did she file for further marital rights, Phillips argued. "Actions speak louder than words," Phillips told the court.</P>

<P>Phillips countered accusations by the estate that the Carolyn and Jerry Garcia's marriage was a sham by describing Carolyn as a woman who was very involved in her marriage and committed to her husband. The estate has stressed that through most of their relationship, Carolyn and Jerry didn't live together. Phillips pointed out that Jerry never lived with his third wife, Deborah Koons Garcia, the executor of the estate.</P>

<P>Phillips concluded by saying that if Jerry Garcia were still alive, the settlement agreement would still be honored and there would be no reason for them to be in court. </P>

<P>The attorney for the estate, Paul Camera, argued that the settlement agreement does not qualify as a contract under California law. The 13-line document is not specific enough to be enforceable, he said. The agreement lacks an  explicit waiver of spousal support, an itemization of assets covered by the agreement, and makes no mention of tax payments. </P>

<P>Camera read correspondences between Carolyn Garcia's and Jerry Garcia's attorneys to show that the attorneys considered the May 11, 1993 agreement to be a "proposed" marital settlement. Camera insisted that Jerry Garcia had no idea what community property Carolyn was entitled to when he signed the agreement, did not have full knowledge of what he was doing, and therefore shouldn't be bound to the agreement. </P>

<P>The contract negotiations were further tainted by David Hellman, Jerry Garcia personal attorney of 20 years, who colluded with Carolyn Garcia, Camera said. </P>

<P>Carolyn Garcia pestered Garcia to marry her, Camera argued, and when that wasn't enough, David Hellman urged a wedding for tax purposes. Camera accused Carolyn of deliberately distancing herself from Hellman to conceal their efforts to manipulate Garcia; efforts that began in the early 1980s and continued all the way up until the settlement agreement.</P>

<P>Camera described Carolyn's credibility as "worthless" and said she deliberately mislead the judge about the date of a letter to make him think she and Garcia had a loving relationship.</P>

<P>In rebuttal, Phillips defended David Hellman, saying the estate was accusing Hellman of perjury without evidence.</P>
