<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV News</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<H2>Lighting Up, But Not Laid Back</H2><P>

By Mike McKee<BR>
<I>The Recorder</I><BR>
January 3, 1997<P>

Alone on a sofa in a corner of the cavernous smoking room of a Mission District marijuana buyers' club, "Animal" Joe Smith takes a hit off the joint he just rolled by hand.<P>

The cheery 34-year-old, who says pot gave him the appetite to regain 18 pounds lost to HIV last summer, sounds like the public relations officer for the club called Flower Therapy: He lauds the stress-free environment, the interaction with other medicinal smokers and the ability "to regularly obtain good, quality marijuana in an atmosphere that's relatively safe."<P>

Yet like others at the 17th Street club, Smith knows that state and federal law enforcement officials are waiting and watching, ready to pounce on buyers' clubs and their patrons at any moment.<P>

"Even with the passage of Prop 215, I don't trust that [California Attorney General] Dan Lungren has my best interests at heart," Smith says as he takes another drag. "I'm still looking over my shoulder when I come in the door."<P>

Smith, a musician and one-time performance artist who contracted HIV four years ago, could very well be speaking for the wary operators of a half-dozen clubs that have quietly sprouted up in San Francisco over the last five months, supplying marijuana to people who claim it alleviates the symptoms of their illnesses. The clubs, which might have been expected to experience newfound freedom when voters approved Proposition 215 in November, have instead functioned like fortresses under fire.<P>

Rather than loosening up, most clubs -- hearing the war drums from Sacramento and Washington, D.C., grow louder -- have tightened up, establishing stringent membership criteria that exceed what's required by the medical marijuana initiative.<P>

Most controversial are buyers' club documents requiring doctors to go public with their names and license numbers if they favor marijuana for patients, even though Prop 215 legalized verbal recommendations. This at a time when the Clinton administration has targeted doctors -- the clubs' most critical allies -- as the weak link in the medical marijuana chain because many fear getting their licenses yanked for recommending pot.<P>

"It's had a chilling effect on the physicians who are willing to step forward," says Berkeley psychiatrist Tod Mikuriya, a longtime advocate of medicinal marijuana who regularly posts his opinions on the Internet. "[Club operators are] playing doctor and defeating the whole reason the initiative was put on the ballot."<P>

The new rules at pot clubs also have created a schism with some of the movement's most outspoken leaders, who call the paperwork barriers overkill.<P>

"The powers that be [in Sacramento and Washington] are attempting to create a climate where people will accept limits that Prop 215 didn't want in place," says John Entwistle Jr., legislative advocate for Californians for Compassionate Use, a grass-roots organization in San Francisco that's largely responsible for Prop 215. "And some clubs are accepting [those limits] because of fear."<P>

Club operators, though, insist that -- with federal and state authorities breathing down their necks -- they would be foolhardy to take unnecessary risks.<P>

"We need paper. We need proof," says John Hudson, founder of Flower Therapy. "It's accountability. I know that much from my lawyer."<P>

WISE MOVE OR PARANOIA?<BR>
Hudson and others have ample reason to worry. State law enforcement officials have vowed to crack down on buyers' clubs, arguing Prop 215 didn't legalize pot sales but rather only lets patients use doctor-recommended marijuana grown by themselves or their ill-defined caregivers.<P>

Federal authorities contributed to mounting fears recently by announcing plans to prosecute buyers' clubs as large-scale distributors and also threatening to arrest cooperating doctors or strip them of their federally granted prescription powers.<P>

"The proposition made no provisions whatsoever about sale," says Stan Vegar, a spokesman for the San Francisco office of the federal Drug Enforcement Administration. "Sale at any level is illegal."<P>

Hoping to head off disaster, most buyers' clubs now demand that potential clients produce valid identification, an official medical diagnosis and a recent letter -- signed by doctors on letterhead stationery and bearing their license number -- recommending marijuana. They also require pot-seekers to sign medical release forms and promise in writing not to resell or distribute the clubs' wares.<P>

Nearly all the clubs say they also call prospective members' doctors to confirm diagnoses, then verify the physician's credentials with the Medical Board of California to ferret out phonies fabricated by narcotics officers looking for a bust. State agents raided San Francisco's original Cannabis Buyers' Club on Market Street in August, driven partly by sales to undercover cops claiming recommendations by nonexistent doctors.<P>

Club operators don't intend to get fooled again.<P>

"The paperwork is to cover our ass so we're not accused of selling to people who don't need [marijuana] medically," says epidemiologist Vic Hern ndez, founder of a club called CHAMP -- Cannabis Helping Alleviate Medical Problems -- near Church and Market streets. "People want assurance that this is going to be a safe place."<P>

Hernandez is following the advice of Pillsbury Madison & Sutro partner Thomas Loran III, who strongly advocates comprehensive record-keeping.<P>

"We feel that we have to document, to some extent, who we are giving [marijuana] to, the medical basis for it and the fact that this is being recommended by a health care provider who is a physician," says Loran, who represents CHAMP pro bono. "[But] we are aware that physicians will increasingly become reluctant to be identified."<P>

The conservative approach of most clubs upsets the top dogs of the medical marijuana movement, who don't want Prop 215 undermined by their own allies.<P>

"It's intimidating doctors and I think that's wrong, and it's intimidating patients and I think that's wrong," says Dennis Peron, director of Californians for Compassionate Use and founder of the original Cannabis Buyers' Club, which is still fighting Lungren in court. "It's a wave of paranoia and paranoia is by definition irrational fear."<P>

Peron notes that while his cannabis club always demanded a medical diagnosis from pot-seekers, it never required "interrogating your doctor." And he doesn't intend to start doing that on Jan. 15, when he reincarnates his current business near the Civic Center as the Cannabis Cultivators' Club.<P>

"We're on the honor system here," he says. "You tell us your doctor recommends marijuana and that's fine with us. I'm not going to put up any impediment."<P>

Hudson, Hernandez and most other club founders favor what could be called aggressive caution -- making sure marijuana is available to the needy, but conceding that legal dangers exist. Yet Peron and Entwistle, inspired by the fact that Prop 215 was approved by a whopping 56 percent, don't see any reason to make patients or doctors jump through extra hoops, and they dare the government to make trouble now that the initiative is on the books as Health & Safety Code 11362.5.<P>

"Dan Lungren's taking advantage of ignorance of the law," Entwistle says, "and his ability to create a climate of fear."<P>

NOT-SO-BRAVE NEW WORLD<BR>
Many allies of Entwistle and Peron admire their daring, but are concerned that the duo is blithely stepping into legal hot water by vowing to accept verbal recommendations.<P>

"That's kind of crazy," says Jeff Jones, director of the Oakland Cannabis Buyers' Club. "I've always been behind Dennis in what he has done, being in the forefront, but I don't support that [particular] judgment. With Dennis not taking paperwork, how's he going to keep track?"<P>

Jones also feels that Peron's approach lets doctors hide behind their patients.<P>

"I want the doctor to get involved with the person [he's] treating," Jones says, "to be, in a word, part of the 'conspiracy.'"<P>

That's a sacrifice most doctors aren't willing to make yet. The majority, in fact, still refuse to acknowledge the new law, period.<P>

"A patient has to understand that while I'll do [almost] anything I can to help him, there comes a point where I won't jeopardize my license by giving him something that's illegal federally," says Dr. Melvin Kirschner, a Van Nuys family practitioner who's also chairman of the Los Angeles medical and bar associations' Joint Committee on Biomedical Ethics. "Either you do it for good legal reasons or you don't do it."<P>

Even doctors like Berkeley's Mikuriya, who admits recommending marijuana to 178 people, has begun taking steps toward self-preservation.<P>

"I'm tightening up my interview procedure and videotaping every applicant -- and taking a still photo ID picture," he says. "They are going to have to have verifiable medical documentation from some other facility. It's beyond paranoia."<P>

Doctors might get a break in San Francisco, though, where District Attorney Terence Hallinan says he'd be willing to set up a procedure allowing doctors to remain anonymous.<P>

"Everybody would prefer [that doctors put their recommendations in writing], but I understand the legal situation," Hallinan says, "and it would be acceptable to me if [a patient] signed an affidavit under penalty of perjury that you have a recommendation by a doctor."<P>

This touchy issue is already playing out in a Sonoma County case, in which a man who says he needs pot to control his epilepsy is being prosecuted on possession and cultivation charges.<P>

In what is believed to be the first such ruling since Prop 215 was passed, a judge on Dec. 17 rejected defendant Alan Martinez's request that his doctor be allowed to testify anonymously that he had recommended marijuana. Oakland solo practitioner William Panzer had argued that the unidentified doctor could testify about his recommendation either _in camera_ in the judge's chambers or by redacting his name from documents filed under seal.<P>

But Municipal Court Judge Mark Tansil said no, explaining that he was "confident" doctors would "testify on direct and cross-examination in the open light of this court."<P>

Panzer says he plans to ask the superior court to review Tansil's decision.<P>

SAFE HOUSES<BR>
Despite the differences among the movement's leaders -- and in spite of threats by state AG Lungren and Clinton administration drug czar Barry McCaffrey to shut clubs down -- smokers are continuing to find a measure of peace in buyers' clubs that they would never have elsewhere.<P>

The clubs are, in effect, safe houses.<P>

"The value of a place like this is not limited to the merchandise," "Animal" Joe Smith says in the confines of Flower Therapy. "We talk to each other. We boost each other. We trade treatment ideas."<P>

A few people at Flower Therapy one day last month said they had faced doctors who wouldn't recommend marijuana for fear of federal retribution or who OK'd it only after seeing improvements in patients who acquired pot on the streets. A 35 -year-old man, diagnosed with stomach cancer and epilepsy, says his physician said no three times before witnessing his patient's weight blossom from 111 pounds to 161.<P>

"He didn't think it would help, but then he saw how much bigger I got, and he wrote out the letter of diagnosis," says the man, who requests anonymity. "He put his doctor's license [number] and his name on the document."<P>

Several doctors must be braving crackdowns, because Hern ndez estimates that about 50 people a day pass through his club, above a gay bar called the Transfer. Hudson says Flower Therapy, in a converted appliance repair shop just off South Van Ness Avenue, attracts as many as 150 a day.<P>

At Flower Therapy, registration forms and medical marijuana literature are displayed up front, and a glass counter further back showcases packets of marijuana -- obtained from "growers up north" -- and assorted pot-laced baked goods, such as brownies and banana bread, going two for five dollars. A chalkboard lists leaf prices, ranging this particular day from eight dollars for an eighth of an ounce of Mexican brown to $60 for an eighth of the second-best variety of California green. The top grade is sold out.<P>

Smokers who make a purchase -- and almost all do once clearing the admissions process -- can then retire to a huge, but comfortable, back room to clean, roll and inhale. There's an easy comradeship evident, with informal gatherings of two or more people around a room that's reminiscent of a John Waters movie set. Warm greetings are exchanged among regulars and just about everyone is eager to cuss out the government or discuss the wonders of marijuana.<P>

There's 51-year-old Jim Scott, for example, who says he smokes pot to combat unipolar mania -- which he describes as a chemical imbalance of the brain that makes him constantly manic. No pharmaceutical, he claims, has helped as much as marijuana.<P>

"When I smoke a joint like this," Scott says, holding up a smoldering hand-wrapped reefer, "I won't call a travel agent and book a flight to Hawaii [for no reason]. I'll go over to my bed, lie down and cocoon. As my doctor says, 'Give him a joint. It keeps his mouth shut.'"<P>

"Mama Tee," a former nurse whose proper name is Latangalia Carr, says she uses pot to counteract the ill effects of taking 12 pills a day for the HIV she says she contracted from a needle stick years ago.<P>

"No way in the world -- as sick as they make me -- that I could take them all without my marijuana," the spicy 51-year-old says matter-of-factly. "After I say, 'Thank you, Lord,' each morning for letting me be alive with my six T-cells, the first thing I do is smoke my marijuana so I can eat and take my anti -virals. If I don't smoke, I don't eat, I don't take my anti -virals and I die. It's a vicious circle."<P>

SICK OR DRUNK?<BR>
Yet what constitutes an illness treatable by marijuana remains debatable too. Prop 215 left the question wide open, allowing treatment for cancer, anorexia, AIDS, chronic pain, spasticity, glaucoma, arthritis, migraines and "any other illness for which marijuana provides relief."<P>

Most clubs interpret the statute broadly, approving diagnoses for things as questionable as stress, insomnia, alcoholism and drug addiction. While admitting that most voters probably didn't envision alcoholics as the recipients of medical marijuana, club operators point out that alcoholism is an officially recognized disease.<P>

"All you have to do is look back at the medical literature from the 19th century to see the effectiveness of cannabis substitution for alcohol," says Dr. Mikuriya of Berkeley. "It's a very good substitute clinically. Anytime you want to take a drink, turn on [to pot] instead and take your antabuse pill."<P>

No less an advocate than Peron himself uses marijuana to control drinking. "I'm an alcoholic," he says flatly. "If it wasn't for marijuana, I'd probably be dead."<P>

Buyers' clubs might face a backlash in the next month, though. There is talk in Sacramento of Republican legislation aimed at curbing the number of illnesses covered by Prop 215. Very likely, treating alcoholics with marijuana -- a process called "harm reduction" -- wouldn't make the cut.<P>

That would be especially detrimental to clubs like CHAMP, whose founder, Hern ndez, has fully embraced the concept in hope of weaning addicts -- particularly the gays who make up a good percentage of his clientele -- off more serious drugs.<P>

"Speed and heroin are big problems in our community," Hern ndez says.<P>

Even on the question of using pot to help break addictions to stronger drugs, there are differences of opinion among the clubs. Hudson and Peron agree with Hern ndez, but Jones of the Oakland club isn't ready to start authorizing marijuana for addicts, even though he recognizes that alcoholism can lead to a painful death.<P>

"We're kind of on the border of whether we're going to push the envelope on harm reduction," says Jones, whose 800 -member club is composed mostly of people with HIV or AIDS. "We're going to wait for the new year to come in and feel it out."<P>

The language of Prop 215 gives doctors a lot of discretion.<P>

"The proposition says 'any ailment' that might be helped by [marijuana]," DA Hallinan says. "That could be the famous hangnail, but I know that [Lungren] is thinking about much more serious illness and I think that's what people were thinking about [when they voted], but that's not what the Prop says. I'd be satisfied if it's decided between the doctor and the patient."<P>

But few people on either side of the issue expect anything to be resolved without going to court. A club will have to be charged with illegal sales or distribution, they say, or a doctor will be accused of dispensing an unlawful substance.<P>

Only then will it be possible to find out whether Prop 215's mandate by the people outweighs the federal government's power to outlaw certain substances.<P>

Doctors might be safe, some attorneys say, because approving or recommending the use of marijuana might not technically violate federal laws prohibiting the "facilitation" of unauthorized drugs. On the other hand, says one lawyer, buyers' clubs might be vulnerable outside certain bounds because "Prop 215 does not clearly allow distribution."<P>

Not surprisingly, though, there are doctors and club members who would welcome a chance to serve as a test defendant -- people like Berkeley's Mikuriya and buyers' club member Eugene Morris -- a walking artifact from the Haight-Ashbury of the '60s who says he uses pot for asthma, emphysema and cancer.<P>

"I'm almost 60 years old and I've been [smoking pot medically] for 10 years," the gray-haired, ponytailed Morris says one day at Flower Therapy. "I'd love for them to arrest me because I'd fight them. I'd have to buy on the streets [if not for the clubs] and risk arrest anyway."<P>

Buyers' club operators hope it doesn't come to that. But in the face of almost institutionalized resistance to any legalization of marijuana, they aren't holding their breath.<P>

"We're trying to give birth to a new industry," says Entwistle, of Californians for Compassionate Care, "and [the government's] trying to put us in the paradigm of trying to get away with a crime. That's not right."<P>

SIDEBAR: CITIES MOVING AHEAD ON PROP 215<P>

By Mike McKee<P>

As the state and federal governments intensified their opposition this week to medicinal marijuana, San Francisco and Oakland city officials quietly worked with pro-pot forces on ways to implement Proposition 215.<P>

Negotiations aimed at establishing a legal framework to distribute pot have been under way since shortly after voters approved the medical marijuana measure on Nov. 5, according to spokespersons for both cities and marijuana buyers' club operators and their attorneys. The hope, they said, is to implement uniform guidelines that will curb potential abuses and provide a foundation for medical necessity defenses for users who get arrested for possession.<P>

"It's a medical issue," said San Francisco District Attorney Terence Hallinan. "So I've asked the Health Department to come up with protocols [and] I've approached the Board of Supervisors about a licensing provision that would allow me to [regulate] the means by which persons can receive marijuana under Prop 215."<P>

Hallinan said he would demand that buyers' clubs verify illnesses, have "strong rules" regarding children's access to marijuana, and abide by other state and local laws.<P>

"I have had one meeting with [club operators]," he said. "I'm aware of their feelings and positions."<P>

Hallinan said he has asked that the Health Department have its recommendations ready in the next week or so.<P>

Pillsbury Madison & Sutro partner Thomas Loran III, who provides pro bono representation to a club called CHAMP -- Cannabis Helping Alleviate Medical Problems -- said Hallinan has assured clubs he won't prosecute, "provided that our clients conduct themselves in a responsible manner."<P>

Loran said it's essential that the clubs work with Hallinan "to establish ways to enable us to have the requisite accountability."<P>

Buyers' clubs in San Francisco and Oakland already have provided members with cards bearing telephone numbers that police can call to verify medical status. "They call me and I'll come running with their paperwork," said John Hudson, founder of San Francisco's Flower Therapy buyers' club.<P>

"We're sort of at the point that the use of medical marijuana is a low [arrest] priority," said Michele Molotsky, chief of staff for Oakland Councilman Nate Miley. "Now we want to look at transportation and distribution. But I have no idea what we're going to do."<P>

Heller Ehrman White & McAuliffe partner Jonathan Hayden, who's working pro bono on implementation issues with a San Francisco-based policy research institute called The Lindesmith Center, praised the local efforts.<P>

"It's clear that they are trying to set these up to be as well documented and clearly run on a medical or pharmaceutical model as possible," Hayden said. The Lindesmith Center, he added, is focusing on ways to protect doctors who recommend marijuana for patients.<P>

"There's a lot of uncertainty out there [in regard to doctors' risks]," he said, "and all we're trying to do is figure out where the best place is to provide some support so this statute can be implemented in a way the people intended it to be."<P>

Meanwhile, buyers' clubs are proceeding cautiously, with attorneys advising them not only to keep good records, but also to account for every pound of their marijuana and to have all their routine daily affairs in order.<P>

"What I've done is take an extremely conservative approach," said San Francisco solo practitioner Matthew Kumin, who advises Flower Therapy. "I'm trying to make sure that like any small business they comply with all the things all small businesses have to deal with -- all of the mundane things that otherwise could be a source, or an excuse, for a government authority to shut an organization down."<P>

The leaders of local buyers' clubs said they plan to continue working with Bay Area officials because it fits their plans.<P>

"We have no national ambitions. Californians for Compassionate Use does not plan to do an initiative in Ohio next year," said John Entwistle Jr., legislative advocate for the San Francisco-based pro-medical marijuana organization. "Our whole goal is to influence the world by local action and to let the world see the benefit to California."<P>

--<I>Associate editor Mike McKee's e-mail address is <a href=mailto:mmckee@counsel.com>mmckee@counsel.com</a><P>

The Recorder is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
