<H2>Firm Has Friends on Both Sides of Apple-Next Merger</H2> <P>

By Krysten Crawford<BR>
<I>The Recorder</I><BR>
January 6, 1997<P>

Apple Computer Inc.'s recent reunion with co-founder Steven Jobs and his company, Next Software Inc., was a prime example of how quickly business alliances change in Silicon Valley.<P>

But the $400 million merger also illustrates how lawyers often change sides in the volatile high-tech world.<P>

Next's lawyers in the merger -- Wilson, Sonsini, Goodrich & Rosati -- had taken Apple public in 1980 and were on hand when the company ousted Jobs in 1985.<P>

Later in 1985, Apple declined to waive a conflict when Jobs tried to hire Wilson, Sonsini to incorporate Next.<P>

"Apple felt it was a conflict and so did I," said Wilson, Sonsini partner Larry Sonsini.<P>

Though Wilson, Sonsini has continued to advise Apple on corporate and other matters, within the past two years the firm has been allowed to step in as Next's chief outside corporate firm.<P>

For instance, Wilson, Sonsini was gearing up to take Next public when the Apple courtship scuttled that plan. In addition, Sonsini now serves as a director of Pixar Inc., a computer animation company launched by Jobs, and also represents Pixar in its corporate dealings.<P>

So when it came time to choose teams to represent the two companies in merger talks, Sonsini's firm was the obvious choice for Next. And this time, Apple did not object to Wilson, Sonsini's role.<P>

Apple, for its part, turned to the San Francisco office of New York's Shearman & Sterling.<P>

Shearman & Sterling first represented Apple in securities litigation a few years ago. More recently, Apple has been using the San Francisco office for some of its big corporate needs, including a much-needed $660 million private placement completed last summer.<P>

"Shearman & Sterling has been representing us in significant corporate matters for a couple of years now," said Susan Thorner, Apple's director of corporate law and a player in the Apple-Next talks.<P>

Despite its work for Apple, Shearman & Sterling also has indirect links to Next: The firm was acting as underwriters' counsel in preparations for Next's initial public offering.<P>

Nancy Heinen, the general counsel at Next, said Shearman & Sterling requested an informal waiver and that she was more than happy to oblige, given the time pressure to cut a deal once talks accelerated early last month. An agreement was announced Dec. 20.<P>

"I don't think we could have done the deal that quickly if we had to add new players to the team," said Heinen, who worked on the transaction with associate general counsel Christopher Palermo.<P>

Besides the changes in outside counsel, the deal also marks a turning point for Heinen, who joined Next three years ago from Tandem Computers Inc. She said she does not expect to join Apple's in-house corps when the merger, which is awaiting federal antitrust approval, reaches its expected conclusion later this month.<P>

"I'm going to close the deal and assist in any transition matters," said Heinen. "Then I'm going to play with my kids for a few months."<P>

<I>The Recorder is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
