<H2>Tobacco Takes a Hit</H2><P>

By Steven Fromm<BR>
<I>The Connecticut Law Tribune</I><BR>
January 6, 1997<P>

For the first time in five months, Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal needn't cast a worried glance at his legal flank in his ongoing war with the tobacco industry.<P>

In a decision described by lawyers involved in the case as a first of its kind, U.S. District Court Judge Peter C. Dorsey dismissed a pre-emptive suit filed by four tobacco industry giants seeking to block Blumenthal from filing a $1 billion suit against them.<P>

In granting Blumenthal's motion to dismiss Philip Morris Inc. v. Blumenthal, Dorsey made it clear that federal courts have no business interfering with state litigation involving an "important state interest."<P>

Dorsey also wasted no time in explaining why he dismissed Philip Morris, while earlier this year a U.S. district judge in Massachusetts did not dismiss a similar action -- Philip Morris v. Harshbarger -- against the Bay State's attorney general.<P>

In Connecticut's action, Blumenthal is using the Connecticut Unfair Trade Practices Act (CUTPA) and state antitrust laws to recoup damages. Dorsey deems those "important state interests" that federal courts have no right to pre-empt. The Massachusetts case did not allege similar consumer protection and antitrust violations.<P>

Also, Dorsey took the time in his nine-page decision -- made on Dec. 23 and released on Dec. 26 -- to blast the tobacco companies that filed Philip Morris for mis-citing cases and using "faulty logic."<P>

Philip Morris Inc. v. Blumenthal was filed in U.S. District Court in Bridgeport on June 28 by Philip Morris Inc. and Lorillard Tobacco Co., both based in New York, the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. of Winston-Salem, N.C., and the Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp. of Louisville, Ky.<P>

The suit was clearly a pre-emptive strike, filed just weeks after Blumenthal announced his intention of filing his own suit against the tobacco industry to recoup state funds spent on smoking-related illnesses, including Medicaid expenditures.<P>

The tobacco companies charged in their suit that Blumenthal's impending action would have an "enormous and far-reaching" impact that could slam the industry with a "retroactive, unprecedented and devastating financial burden."<P>

The foursome contended that Connecticut's planned suit would "significantly impede interstate commerce" of a legal product -- cigarettes.<P>

Similar actions were filed in Texas, Massachusetts and Maryland. All four states have filed suits against the tobacco industry.<P>

Describing the tobacco companies' suit as an "effort to bully and intimidate my office," Blumenthal, aided by a small coalition of Connecticut law firms chosen by him, filed a $1 billion suit against the tobacco industry on July 18.<P>

Blumenthal's action, Connecticut v. Philip Morris Inc., is the largest civil action ever filed by the state.<P>

Connecticut won an early-round victory on Oct. 15, when U.S. District Judge Janet B. Arterton denied a motion by the tobacco companies to have Philip Morris tried in federal court, instead of where it is now pending -- in the state Superior Court in Litchfield before Judge Michael R. Sheldon.<P>

JUST THE BEGINNING<BR>
Dorsey's decision may be a clear victory for Blumenthal and his coalition, but it is far from the end of the battle.<P>

"The most important thing is that the essence of our position is that we are going to defend this case," says Michael M. York, of the Washington, D.C.-based Wehner & York, which represents Philip Morris Inc.<P>

"We honestly believe that there is no legal merit at all to the legal claims asserted by the attorney general," York says. "One of the most profound constitutional issues of due process is do tobacco companies enjoy the due-process rights at all in these types of lawsuits."<P>

York asserts that "stripped of all their exotic consumer protection and antitrust claims, the attorney general's action alleges one thing: The [tobacco] companies are to be held liable for alleged injuries to third parties on the basis of one act -- the lawful sale of a legal product."<P>

David S. Golub, a partner with Stamford-based Silver, Golub & Teitell -- one of the firms working with the state in Philip Morris -- sees the issue differently.<P>

"The issue is not the legal right to something, they [the tobacco companies] do have that right," Golub says. "The issue is whether they have misrepresented the nature of the product, and if they have been manipulating the addictive nature of the products. If you violate the law in the way you market it, you can be held liable."<P>

Golub is now looking forward to the battle in state Superior Court.<P>

"What we really think will happen now is that the case in state court will move ahead," Golub says. "We are getting 200,000 documents from the defendants. They will start coming in in the beginning of January, and we are really going to litigate the case aggressively."<P>

The other Connecticut firms to make up the coalition, in addition to Golub's, are Waterbury's Carmody & Torrance and Stamford's Emmett & Glander. The Philadelphia firm of Berger & Montague is also part of the coalition.<P>

"The linchpin of this powerful and profound precedent is the court's conclusion that an important state interest is at stake," Attorney General Richard Blumenthal notes in a written statement released right after Dorsey's decision. "This court is the first to reach that conclusion, which is absolutely correct and critical to litigation around the country."<P>

But the tobacco companies are also still hoping to carry their fight -- or at least a part of it -- to the federal courts.<P>

"We want the federal [constitutional] issues [raised in Philip Morris v. Blumenthal] decided in a federal court," York says. "What we are doing is starting to analyze [Dorsey's] ruling to determine if we should seek review in the Court of Appeals. This case is similar to the one in Massachusetts, and that judge reached the opposite result. If necessary, we will have the opportunity to have the issue resolved in that court."<P>

But Dorsey's ruling is blunt enough to be of some reassurance to Blumenthal and company.<P>

Right off the bat, Dorsey notes in his decision that the "tobacco companies' action raises the issue of federal court interference with pending state legislation."<P>

Dorsey points to a key 1971 U.S. Supreme Court decision, Younger v. Harris, which notes that "since the beginning of this country's history Congress has, subject to few exceptions, manifested a desire to permit state courts to try state cases free from interference by federal courts."<P>

The Younger court also ruled that "the normal thing to do when federal courts are asked to enjoin pending proceedings in state courts is not to issue such injunctions."<P>

However, Dorsey also notes that "[a]lthough Younger addressed federal actions to enjoin state criminal proceedings, the same principles of comity mandate extreme caution before enjoining certain kinds of state civil proceedings as well."<P>

Abstention under Younger is appropriate when: "1) there is an ongoing state proceeding; 2) an important state interest is implicated; and 3) the plaintiff has an avenue open for review of constitutional claims in the state court," Dorsey states, citing a 1992 decision, Hansel v. Town Court for Town of Springfield, from the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 2nd Circuit.<P>

"When these conditions are met," Dorsey notes,  "abstention is obligatory."<P>

"There is clearly an ongoing state proceeding in the present case," Dorsey adds. "The question is whether this element requires that the state proceedings be brought before the federal action. The typical scenario, as in Younger, is that the state action came first."<P>

Still, Dorsey notes that in a 1975 case, Hicks v. Miranda, the U.S. Supreme Court held that Younger also applies in cases where the federal action was filed pre-emptively.<P>

TOBACCO'S TACTIC<BR>
But the tobacco companies argue that a 1974 U.S. Supreme Court case, Steffel v. Thompson -- not Hicks -- is the key case that applies to Philip Morris Inc. v. Blumenthal.<P>

Under Steffel, federal courts need not abstain under Younger if there is no pending state proceeding.<P>

"However," Dorsey writes, "Steffel applies when there is no pending state proceeding. The Supreme Court in Hicks specifically distinguished that scenario from one in which there is a pending state proceeding which, in a race to the courthouse, happened to be filed second."<P>

Dorsey notes that in Philip Morris, the tobacco companies attempt to distinguish Hicks on several other grounds. They argue that Hicks applies only to criminal, not civil, proceedings.<P>

Dorsey doesn't buy it.<P>

"This argument is without merit," he writes. "As discussed above, Younger applies to certain types of civil actions. Hicks applies to civil proceedings to the same extent that Younger does."<P>

Finally, the tobacco companies argue that "comity works both ways": Respect for federalism would have the state court, not the federal court, abstain. To bolster their argument, the tobacco companies cite a 1995 case out of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 1st Circuit, Chaulk Services v. Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination.<P>

Dorsey pricks this legal balloon as well.<P>

"In Chaulk, the state administrative action interfered with a federal statutory and administrative system constitutionally adopted by [c]ongress," Dorsey writes. "There is no such federal administrative pre-emption in the present action. Accordingly, there is an `ongoing proceeding' for Younger purposes."<P>

EYEING STATE INTERESTS<BR>
Dorsey adds muscle to his ruling by noting that abstention by the federal courts is "proper under Younger in civil cases only if the proceedings implicate `important state interests,' " under yet another U.S. Supreme Court decision, 1982's Middlesex Ethics Comm. v. Garden State Bar Association.<P>

"The attorney general's claims under the Connecticut Unfair Trade Practices Act (CUTPA) and under Connecticut antitrust law are important state interests," Dorsey rules. "Both claims are under statutory schemes which contemplate civil enforcement actions by state authorities to effect state policy."<P>

Dorsey adds that "[t]hese laws are mechanisms for the state to enforce its important interest in fair trade in Connecticut."<P>

The tobacco companies urged Dorsey to follow Harshbarger, the Massachusetts case. Again, Dorsey completely rejects their argument.<P>

"The Massachusetts District Court declined to abstain under Younger because it did not find an important state interest," Dorsey notes. "The Massachusetts Attorney General's action, which sought reimbursement for Medicaid expenditures, was found to be `classically in the nature of subrogation,' and accordingly not an important state interest.<P>

"However, Harshbarger must be distinguished because the Massachusetts Attorney General's suit in state court did not allege violations of state unfair trade practice and antitrust law, as does the Connecticut state court action," he writes. "It is therefore unnecessary to address the merits and applicability of Harshbarger, since the Attorney General's CUTPA and antitrust claims do implicate an important state interest."<P>

The tobacco companies attempt, in the words of Dorsey, to "gloss over" the absence of unfair trade practice and antitrust claims in the Massachusetts case by pointing out that the underlying state complaints in the two cases are "predicated on virtually identical factual allegations."<P>

"This argument misses the point," Dorsey notes. "The existence of an important state interest for Younger purposes does not depend on whether the relief sought is monetary or injunctive. Rather, it depends on the nature of the claim brought in the underlying state court action."<P>

The tobacco companies also argue that claims in the federal action, which seek injunctions against imposition of liability for future, as opposed to past, sales of tobacco, should not be barred under Younger.<P>

This argument, which Dorsey describes as "puzzling," draws the judge's sharpest comments.<P>

"This argument is based on mis-cited cases and faulty logic," he says. ". . . There furthermore is no logical base to this argument. Nothing indicates that the state court would take the unprecedented step of imposing liability for sales which have not yet occurred." Powerful or Procedural?<P>

"The CUTPA count made a really big difference [between the outcome of the Connecticut and Massachusetts cases], and there wasn't an antitrust count in the Massachusetts case, either," Golub says.<P>

"The judge up there said, `This is just a case for Medicaid funds, it's just like any other case for money, so we don't need to dismiss this [the tobacco companies]' case," he adds. "We were able to say, even if you think the Massachusetts case is right, ours is not just a case for money. We are seeking broad remedial relief under important sovereign statutes."<P>

Edward F. Hennessey, of Hartford's Robinson & Cole, which is representing R.J. Reynolds, notes that, "I think it was a surprise to some in the sense that it was a different outcome than what occurred in Massachusetts."<P>

"But as far as having a real impact, I don't think it will," Hennessey adds. "Our case is before Judge Sheldon, and no one on either side questions his ability to handle this. [The federal case] was strictly a procedural decision. It did not resolve anything other than a matter of form."<P>

Francis H. Morrison III, of the Hartford office of Day, Berry & Howard, which is representing Brown & Williamson, says that, "I think we are all going to have to study very carefully what he [Dorsey] had to say, and consider where to go from here in the federal action."<P>

Morrison notes that "Judge Dorsey obviously felt the allegations under CUTPA and the Connecticut antitrust statutes made a different. That was really the linchpin decision."<P>

<I>Connecticut Law Tribune is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
Copyright  1997 American Lawyer Media</I><P>

