<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>Court TV News</TITLE> </HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="DD0000"> <A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A> 
<H2>The Tale of Victims' Rights</H2><P>

By Paul G. Cassell and Robert F. Hoyt<Br> 
<I>Legal Times</I><Br> 
December 30, 1996 <P>

The victims' rights movement saw substantial legislative victories in 1996. Voters in eight states approved victims' rights amendments to their constitutions, bringing the total number of states in which victims have constitutional rights to 28. Congress followed suit by introducing a proposed federal constitutional amendment and enacting legislation that reinforced victims' rights to view proceedings related to the prosecution of those charged with crimes against them, even when the trial is moved to another district. <P>

Implementation of these legislative successes, however, left much to be desired. If 1996 was a winning year for victims at the voting booth and in the legislatures, it was all too often a losing year for them in court. In a variety of cases, victims who asserted their newfound rights saw their interests subordinated to the perceived convenience of the courts and the dubious constitutional claims of defendants. <P>

If the victims' rights movement is to make significant progress in 1997, it will have to change the mind- set of criminal justice professionals so that they recognize that victims have important interests and a role to play in the criminal justice process. The only way to guarantee that progress is passage and ratification of the federal Victims Rights Amendment. <P>

The genesis of the success of the victims movement can be traced to the 1982 Final Report of the President's Task Force on Victims of Crime, which criticized the criminal justice system for its neglectful treatment of victims and recommended a range of proposals designed to confer rights on victims. In the years since, the states and Congress have enacted a variety of measures adopting these recommendations. <P>

The state constitutional amendments are a prime example, as is the federal Victims Rights and Restitution Act of 1990 (commonly referred to as the Victims Bill of Rights), which gives crime victims the right to be notified of and present at court proceedings, and to receive information about the conviction, sentencing, imprisonment, and release of the offender. This year, Congress enacted legislation providing for mandatory restitution to crime victims and closed circuit television broadcast of trial proceedings moved far from their original location. <P>

COURTS SLOW TO CHANGE <br>
Notwithstanding these and other important legislative enactments, the pace of acceptance by the judicial system has been agonizingly slow. The trials of Oklahoma City bombing suspects Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols present a high-profile example. Perhaps the most surprising decision to the hundreds of victims of the bombing was the court's ruling on "the rule" on witnesses (Fed. R. Evid. 615). Under the rule, the court held, "victim impact" witnesses at sentencing would not be permitted to attend the trial proceedings in Denver or to watch them in Oklahoma City over closed circuit television. <P>
The victims and the government moved for reconsideration, directing the court to the Victims Bill of Rights, which gives victims the right to be present at "all public court proceedings related to the offense, unless the court determines that testimony by the victim would be materially affected if the victim heard other testimony at trial." Both the victims and the government noted that no finding of material impact had been made, and argued that no such finding could be made with respect to victims whose only testimony would relate the impact of the crime on their own lives. <P>

The court rejected requests for reconsideration, holding that the victims lacked standing even to assert their rights under the federal statute and concluding that the provisions of the statute had no bearing on the court's authority to exclude victims. The affected victims, joined by the government, have sought interlocutory review in the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 10th Circuit (Marsha Kight, et al. v. Hon. Richard P. Matsch, No. 96-1484), with an expedited decision expected in the next month or two. <P>

Other rulings in the Oklahoma City case reflect this same apparent disinterest in the rights that Congress has accorded crime victims. For example, the judge ruled that the defendants would receive separate trials because certain incriminating statements by Nichols were inadmissible against McVeigh. The court quickly skipped over the fact that this ruling would leave the victims' lives on hold for not one long and difficult trial, but two. In determining that two trials were the appropriate result, the court also paid little attention to alternatives that would have eased the burden on the victims while protecting the defendants' rights, such as impaneling two separate juries and excusing the relevant jury from the courtroom on the rare trial days when testimony admissible against only one defendant was presented. <P>

Similarly, in ordering that the trial be relocated to Denver (as opposed to other appropriate locales closer to Oklahoma City), the court apparently paid little attention to the effect on the victims' right to be present. As a result, any victim wishing to attend even a portion of either trial will have to travel hundreds of miles simply to get to the courthouse. Once there, they would find only 12 seats reserved for the hundreds of victims. (The same number were reserved for the families of the two defendants; more than three times as many were reserved for representatives of the media.) <P>

As a partial response to the victims' inability to attend the hearings in Denver, Congress adopted the Televised Proceedings for Crime Victims provision, which requires that a trial court must provide for closed circuit broadcast of trial proceedings held more than 350 miles from the location of the crime (as in the Oklahoma City bombing case). But even this express mandate met with little enthusiasm. It appears that the broadcast will go to a courtroom with an approximate capacity of 150 persons (rather than the largest courtroom in the local federal courthouse or a large auditorium at a nearby military base), and will not be activated until opening arguments. The result is that, despite federal legislation giving victims the right to be present at all proceedings, hundreds of Oklahoma City victims have been, and will continue to be, unable to do so. <P>

Johnson v. Rodriguez (No. 95-50879), a case pending before the 5th Circuit, provides another illustration of the obstacles facing victims. Johnson involves a Texas statute that allows victims to submit confidential statements to the Board of Pardons and Paroles concerning the impact of a crime. It appears that victim statements have had some effect, as sentences served by violent offenders in Texas lengthened in the years after enactment of the statute. <P>

But in a challenge to the law filed by various prisoners, a federal magistrate struck it down as a violation of the equal protection clause of the 14th Amendment because the Parole Board tended, more often than not, to deny parole after receiving input from a victim. In other words, because the victims' input had some real-world effect, the magistrate determined that the statute allowing the input was unconstitutional. The state's appeal of this ruling was heard by the 5th Circuit in November, and the court's decision in 1997 will perhaps be another bellwether in the movement for victims' rights. <P>

END THE UNCERTAINTY <br>
The reluctance of courts to recognize those rights already accorded to crime victims has led to a nationwide cry for an amendment to the U.S. Constitution that would leave no doubt that victims are entitled to fair treatment in the criminal justice process. Proposed by a bipartisan coalition in Congress, the idea has been endorsed by President Bill Clinton and was a plank in the recent platforms of the Republican and Democratic parties. <P>

Once ratified, the proposed Victims Rights Amendment will establish a national "floor" for victims' rights and end the uncertainty that victims now face when they attempt to assert their rights. The amendment will guarantee such basic rights as that to be notified about court hearings, to attend those hearings, and to speak at appropriate points in the process (including at hearings to determine bail, sentencing, or parole). It will also guarantee victims the right to an order of restitution from a convicted offender and to notice before the offender is released from prison. These rights are critical to crime victims and do not conflict with the established constitutional rights of criminal defendants. <P>

The Victims Rights Amendment has already attracted the kind of strong support that is necessary to amend the Constitution. With endorsements from the president and important members of both parties in Congress, and companion amendments in place in more than half the states, the likelihood of passage and ratification seems high. If so, 1997 will be remembered as the year in which our criminal justice system's appalling disregard for the interests of victims was finally brought to an end. <P>

--<I>Paul G. Cassell is a professor of law at the University of Utah College of Law. Robert F. Hoyt is an associate at D.C.'s Wilmer, Cutler & Pickering. Professor Cassell and Wilmer, Cutler represent victims and allied organizations in the Oklahoma City bombing case and in Johnson v. Rodriguez. They also advise the National Victims' Constitutional Amendment Network, a nonprofit group supporting passage of a constitutional amendment according rights to victims of crime. <P>

Legal Times is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
Copyright  1996 American Lawyer Media</I><P>

