<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>Court TV News</TITLE> </HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="DD0000"> <A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A> 

<H2>New Gingrich Counsel: A Rough Welcome</H2><P>

By Don J. DeBenedictis <Br> 
<I>Legal Times</I><Br> 
December 30, 1996 <P>

House Speaker Newt Gingrich's new lawyer in his ethics investigation, J. Randolph Evans, is a longtime Gingrich friend and adviser who is no stranger to tough political fights. His newest assignment may be his toughest yet, as evidenced by the fact that he began drawing fire before he'd even settled into the job. <P>

On Dec. 19, Gingrich announced that Evans would take over duties as the speaker's lead counsel for the ongoing congressional ethics probe, replacing Jan Baran, a veteran Washington ethics and election-law specialist. It did not take long for an old Gingrich foe to take aim at the speaker's choice. <P>

David Worley, an Atlanta lawyer whom Gingrich narrowly defeated in his 1990 re-election campaign, says that Evans may be unable to fulfill his new role because he could become a witness in the House Ethics Committee investigation of Gingrich. <P>

"It is surprising to me that as a potential witness, he could be in a position to represent Gingrich," says Worley. <P>

Evans, who heads the professional negligence defense group at Atlanta's Arnall Golden & Gregory, was Gingrich's campaign chairman in the 1990 race. Worley's charge of a possible conflict grows out of an affidavit that Evans submitted early this year in a suit filed by the Federal Election Commission against Gingrich's political action committee, GOPAC. <P>

In the affidavit, Evans states that the 1990 campaign committee never received "any support, directly or indirectly, financial or otherwise from GOPAC. . . ." <P>

The two-year-old House Ethics Committee investigation of the speaker has focused on charges that Gingrich may have misused money donated to charitable foundations for political purposes, and misled the committee about a college course he taught. <P>

Since he has signed an affidavit related to the case -- denying charges that GOPAC provided "Newt support" to Gingrich's campaign-Evans' testimony could be needed, says Worley, who was an associate at Arnall Golden in the 1980s. <P>

Evans and a Gingrich spokesman did not return calls seeking comment for this article.<P>

But Ralph Lotkin, a former chief counsel to the ethics panel, says the affidavit could indeed raise "interesting conflict problems" -- if it is introduced before the ethics committee "and is in some respects potentially relevant to the committee's investigation of alleged wrongdoing by the speaker." Lotkin is now the managing partner of D.C.'s Cochran & Lotkin. (Lotkin's partner, Johnnie Cochran, is a commentator on Court TV, which has editorial and business ties to Legal Times.) <P>

Lotkin says the document could "place Mr. Evans in the position of being both the attorney-advocate on behalf of Mr. Gingrich and a witness who could supply information potentially detrimental to his client's interests." Lotkin worked on the ethics probe that led to the fall of former Speaker Jim Wright (D-Texas) in 1989. <P>

AFFIDAVIT: GOPAC HURT CAMPAIGN <br>
In the affidavit, Evans said GOPAC not only did not help the Gingrich re-election race, but was actually an "impediment" because it took Gingrich away from the campaign and the district. "His absence from the district was a major contributing factor for the 974-vote margin in the 1990 election," Evans declared. <P>

The affidavit is not dated, but the attestation from a notary public is dated Jan. 2, 1996. The suit, Federal Election Commission v. GOPAC, was dismissed earlier this year by U.S. District Judge Louis Oberdorfer, who said that the FEC had failed to prove that GOPAC had violated federal election law. <P>

William Kitchens, chairman of the management committee at Arnall Golden, says the firm was aware of Evans' filing of the affidavit, and that "proper procedures were followed." He would not comment further on the affidavit or any potential conflict, or on Evans' selection as Gingrich's new ethics defender. <P>

Baran and his firm, D.C.'s Wiley, Rein & Fielding, resigned their representation of Gingrich amid reports that Gingrich had blamed Baran for alleged misstatements about GOPAC made to the ethics committee. <P>

Late last week, however, Baran, former general counsel to the Republican National Committee, and Tony Blankley, Gingrich's press secretary, released a joint statement "to avoid a growing misconception," asserting that Baran and the firm "continue to represent Newt Gingrich"; though "they are no longer representing him directly before the Ethics Committee or its Special Counsel," the statement reads, Baran and the firm "are continuing to assist Newt and others in that proceeding." <P>

This is not Evans' first foray into Washington's ethics battles; he was a key player in an earlier ethics challenge to a speaker of the House-when Gingrich filed an ethics complaint in 1988 against then House Speaker Wright. <P>

Jeffrey Smith of Atlanta's Katz, Smith & Cohen was the head of the malpractice defense group at Arnall Golden at the time; Evans brought him in to help Gingrich go after Wright, Smith says. Smith says he wrote the complaint against Wright. <P>

Two or three other complaints had been drafted but failed to attract support from other Republican House members. But 76 Republicans signed the new complaint within an hour of its being put forward, Smith says. <P>

In a 1988 profile of Evans in the Fulton County Daily Report, a Legal Times affiliate, Gingrich was quoted as calling him "clearly the finest general talent in the Republican Party in Georgia today." <P>

The two met when Evans was a student and Gingrich a geography professor at West Georgia College in Carrollton. Evans worked on the future speaker's first campaign for Congress, and by 1988 was the chairman of the Republican Party in Gingrich's 6th District. Evans even considered running for governor in 1990. <P>

However, he retreated somewhat from heavy political activity as his practice grew, according to partner Charles Huddleston. Evans became head of his practice group at Arnall Golden when Smith left the firm in 1992, according to Smith. <P>

Evans' practice now focuses on work for major insurance carriers, according to partner Jonathan Golden-including advising on coverage in malpractice claims against lawyers, corporate directors and officers, accountants, and engineers. <P>

Golden says Evans travels extensively for his practice and also often speaks on professional negligence. He leads an annual seminar on malpractice defense and is the author of a book on legal malpractice defense now in its fourth edition, according to Golden. <P>

Golden describes his partner as "very analytical" and extremely hard-working. <P>

Evans, 38, offered a similar description of himself in the 1988 Daily Report profile: "My reputation is of being a total and complete workaholic, which is what I am." <P>

He grew up in Warner Robins and attended West Georgia College and the University of Georgia School of Law. <P>

He worked hard there, too, recalls Marietta lawyer and Democratic activist Robert Kahn, who has known him since they were debate opponents in 10th grade. <P>

"He was on moot court and law review at the same time," Kahn recalls. <P>

Kahn says that as an attorney, Evans is aggressive and gives "good attention to detail." <P>

As far as Evans' new client is concerned, Kahn says that Evans has known the speaker for years and knows politics. Says Kahn: "The speaker needs somebody he has full confidence in . . <P>

--<I>Don J. DeBenedictis is associate editor of the Fulton County Daily Report, an affiliate of Legal Times. Senior reporter Timothy J. Burger of Legal Times Contributed to this story. <P>

Legal Times is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
