<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<H2>Escape Routes Slamming Shut For Inmates on Death Row</H2>  <P>

By Naftali Bendavid<BR>
<I>The Recorder</I><BR>
December 27, 1996<P>

WASHINGTON -- This was the year the hangman got serious.<P>

Twenty years after the U.S. Supreme Court reinstated the death penalty, impatient lawmakers in April drastically cut back on death row appeals. Then, for good measure, Congress did away with the 20 federal law offices that help represent the condemned.<P>

Law-and-order enthusiasts are cheering those actions, saying the system is finally free to punish murderers as demanded by justice -- and the people. But advocates for death row inmates warn that the slashing of safeguards is pushing the nation toward an indiscriminate jump in executions, and that inevitably some who die will be innocent.<P>

"It's become clear over the past 20 years that we can have the death penalty or we can have enforcement of the Constitution, but we can't have both," says George Kendall, an attorney with the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund Inc. "The question is, which one are we going to have? And for now, it seems clear that our leaders have said we're going to have the death penalty."<P>

But conservatives insist the streamlining was necessary. "The American people were terribly frustrated with the administration of the criminal justice system," says Paul Kamenar, executive legal director of the nonprofit Washington Legal Foundation. "It is terribly unresponsive to the victim and is skewed extremely on the side of the criminal and the defendant. This is a step in the right direction."<P>

While California carried out two executions this year, more than in any single year since 1962, the death machine nationwide actually slowed a little in 1996 as courts wrestled with the new law: Forty-five people were put to death (no executions are scheduled between now and year's end), compared to last year's 56. But many expect the changes will cause the numbers to soar in coming years, perhaps to more than 100 a year. Currently, roughly 3,200 people reside on death row.<P>

As in the past few years, lethal injection was by far the leading method of execution; electrocutions were a distant second; and there was a hanging in Delaware and a firing squad shooting in Utah.<P>

NEW LAW HASTENS DEATH<BR>
The year's most dramatic development on the capital punishment front was the passage of the law reforming <I>habeas corpus</I>, the process that allows inmates to argue in federal court that they were unconstitutionally tried. Liberals say <I>habeas</I> is crucial to save innocent people from execution; conservatives complain that it is abused by inmates who file multiple appeals in an attempt to stave off their date with death.<P>

The new law -- signed in April after years of conservative crusading -- allows only one appeal in federal court, except under extraordinary circumstances, and the appeal must be filed within one year.<P>

"The <I>habeas</I> bill is one of the all-time most important reinstitutions of criminal law," says Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee. "It was about time we put a stop to the endless, frivolous appeals of justly imposed sentences."<P>

Marc Klaas, whose daughter Polly was sexually abused and murdered in Northern California by Richard Allen Davis, says the new law could shorten by seven years the time he must wait to witness Davis' death. "[Davis] admitted he sexually relieves himself twice a day thinking about victims of his past crimes," Klaas says. "That means Polly will be continually victimized for as long as he lives."<P>

But death penalty opponents say the new law means there is a real danger of the innocent being killed. Criminal trials, they say, are often horribly botched, especially if the defendant is poor. State judges, sensitive to the political winds, often do not correct matters, these activists add, so federal <I>habeas</I> is crucial.<P>

Take Lloyd Schlup, who has been on death row in Missouri since 1984. Schlup was convicted of killing a fellow inmate while serving time on another crime. Years later, a new lawyer found that several eyewitnesses, plus a prison videotape, corroborated Schlup's claim of innocence. In 1995, the U.S. Supreme Court, through the <I>habeas</I> process, gave Schlup another chance to prove his innocence.<P>

Under the new law, Schlup's appeal would not have been allowed, according to Sean O'Brien, executive director of the Public Interest Litigation Clinic in Kansas City, Mo.<P>

"Schlup would be killed under the new statute," says O'Brien, who represented Schlup. "But he's innocent. That's where the law leaves us."<P>

It is difficult at this early stage to find inmates who have already been executed solely due to the new law's speedier timetable. The courts had been showing less patience with <I>habeas</I> petitions anyway. And many cases in which the new law might have come into play are tied up in court.<P>

Indeed, one reason this year's death numbers are not higher is that the Supreme Court announced in early May it would hear a case, <I>Felker v. Turpin</I>, challenging the new <I>habeas</I> law. The case was decided in late June, with the law essentially being upheld. But during that two-month period from May to June, virtually no one was executed.<P>

Many suspect the Supreme Court will soon agree to hear <I>Lindh v. Murphy</I>, decided recently by the Chicago-based Seventh Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, which declared that the new law applies retroactively, to cases already in the pipeline when it was enacted. The ruling also interprets the law as requiring federal judges to give greater deference to state court decisions -- a requirement some say guts the <I>habeas</I> process.<P>

Hatch says he does not expect the new law will lead to a flood of executions. "The new federal <I>habeas corpus</I> law has not created a rush to execute death row inmates, nor will it," the senator says. "The process will still be thorough and deliberate."<P>

LOST RESOURCES<BR>
If the punch of the new <I>habeas</I> law is not yet being fully felt, the elimination of the death penalty resource centers is having a starker effect. These 20 federal law offices, with their 190 lawyers, were defunded by Congress on April 1.<P>

Aside from providing lawyering, the offices kept track of who among the condemned had attorneys, injecting some order into the previously chaotic capital punishment system. Now, say death row advocates, that chaos is returning with a vengeance -- at a time when the intricate new <I>habeas</I> law makes it all the more crucial to have knowledgeable attorneys.<P>

"Now when you have people with the greatest need for legal assistance, you have no lawyers," says Stephen Bright, director of the Southern Center for Human Rights, which represents death row inmates. "It's like Congress passing a huge communications bill and then telling the communications industry, 'You can't have any lawyers to figure out what it means.'"<P>

For example: The Missouri resource center had eight lawyers and three investigators. When it shut down, O'Brien formed the Public Interest Litigation Clinic with private funds -- but it has just three lawyers and one investigator. Its mission: to watch over Missouri's 94 death row inmates.<P>

"I don't think anyone in Missouri got executed while there was a resource center, without us at least looking at the case," says O'Brien. "About half the time, we succeeded in convincing a federal court that the execution was unjust and should not go forward. In the last year, that ratio has been shot to hell."<P>

But critics of the resource centers say they were little more than taxpayer-funded think tanks for the anti-death penalty movement.<P>

"A lot of what they did was duplicative of work that already was being done by other defense counsel," insists Kamenar of the Washington Legal Foundation. "They would just come in as a third or fourth or fifth counsel on the case and not really add anything to it."<P>

Rep. Bob Inglis, R-S.C., who spearheaded the effort to kill the resource centers, agrees. "I am quite certain that the accused are continuing to get effective representation," he says.<P>

TEXAS LAW CHALLENGED<BR>
But many states seem to be having a tough time handling the death penalty smoothly.<P>

Exhibit A: Texas. The state last year passed a law requiring death row inmates to file their direct appeal at the same time as their state <I>habeas</I> appeal, and to do it within 180 days of conviction. In exchange for this streamlined appeal, the state guaranteed defendants appellate lawyers.<P>

That Texas law is now tied up in state court. Meanwhile, virtually no one is being executed in the state.<P>

At the same time, Texas is trying desperately to find lawyers for its 400-plus death row inmates, as its new statute promises. The state's Court of Criminal Appeals recently ordered 48 attorneys to take on death cases -- prompting a mini -rebellion among members of the defense bar. The court chose the lawyers so carelessly that it even named a prosecutor to represent one defendant -- a move it of course had to reverse.<P>

The upshot: Texas' death system, usually the most prolific in the nation, is paralyzed.<P>

Even Hatch acknowledges that defense lawyers in death cases need help. He wants to establish a national training center for lawyers who represent capital defendants.<P>

"I think it benefits everyone if we could get rid of these post-trial motions that say that defense lawyers are incompetent," Hatch says.<P>

So 20 years after the death penalty was re-established by the high court in <I>Gregg v. Georgia</I>, key steps were taken this year in an attempt to make it work better. Some think the death penalty is about to work well at last. But others see it plummeting toward disaster.<P>

About the only thing everyone agrees on, as Bryan Stevenson of Alabama's Equal Justice Initiative points out, is that the death penalty's first 20 years have been a mess. Conservatives are furious that murderers keep delaying their punishment; liberals are upset that, as they see it, the death penalty kills randomly and unfairly.<P>

"There are very few people in this country who would disagree that the whole death penalty experiment has been a failure," says Stevenson, whose group represents death row inmates. "They might disagree as to why, but most folks who have any information or experience would agree it's been a failure."<P>

<I>--Naftali Bendavid is news editor at Legal Times, a Washington-based weekly affiliated with The Recorder.<P>

The Recorder is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
Copyright  1996 American Lawyer Media</i><P>

