<H2>Gun Ban Snares Cops</H2><P>

By Paul Elias<BR>
<I>The Recorder</I><BR>
Dec. 20, 1996<P>

A tough new federal law that bars anyone convicted of misdemeanor spousal abuse from owning or carrying a gun is creating chaos in police and sheriff's departments across the country.<P>

The measure, which amended the Gun Control Act of 1968 to take a hard line against domestic violence, makes no exceptions for law enforcement officials and other government employees whose job requires them to carry a weapon.<P>

Police officers and their union representatives blast the law as unconstitutional, threatening litigation if the gun ban costs officers their jobs. At the same time, law enforcement officials and police agencies are trying to figure out how to comply.<P>

"We are getting 200 to 300 calls a day," said Larry Washington, a special agent with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.<P>

In Dallas the police chief demoted an officer to a nonuniformed jail post, and in Minneapolis the chief demoted or suspended five officers with domestic violence rap sheets.<P>

In California, where some 100 peace officers could be affected, law enforcement officials are hoping to get some guidance from Attorney General Dan Lungren.<P>

Lungren is expected to issue an interpretation of the law in the next few days.<P>

The measure, which took effect Nov. 1, plugs a hole in federal gun control laws that already bar felons from owning firearms. Most domestic violence cases are prosecuted as misdemeanors.<P>

When the legislation was debated in Congress last year, there were few objections to the argument that domestic violence offenders should be barred from owning guns. In fact, California already has a law on the books that says anyone convicted of misdemeanor domestic violence can't own a gun for 10 years, but it gives discretion to waive the prohibition for peace officers.<P>

But what is driving law enforcement officials craziest about the federal ban is a phrase that apparently makes it retroactive. Federal officials say anyone convicted of misdemeanor domestic violence at any time permanently loses the right to carry a gun.<P>

In other words, the law can be applied even if a cop was convicted of misdemeanor domestic violence 20 years ago. The prohibition extends to the military, the National Guard and any other government agency where employees carry arms.<P>

ATF chief John Magaw, in a Nov. 27 letter to every police chief and sheriff in the country, said the ban "applies to persons convicted of such misdemeanors at any time, even if the conviction occurred prior to the new law's effective date."<P>

Internally, ATF is asking any of its officers with misdemeanor domestic violence records to come forward on their own.<P>

Despite Magaw's letter, many officials are still unsure of how to deal with the law and find themselves in a legal wringer.<P>

On the one hand, government lawyers warn that departments may face increased liability if they fail to identify officers with domestic violence records and remove their weapons.<P>

On the other hand, police unions -- at least in the Bay Area -- are threatening to sue the first department that fires a peace officer because of the federal law.<P>

"Nobody condones domestic violence, but this smacks of <I>ex post facto</I>," said Ed Lieberman, a union representative with the Operating Engineers Local 3, which represents more than 3,000 Bay Area peace officers, including 600 San Francisco sheriff's deputies.<P>

But the <I>ex post facto</I> argument is a long shot, some officials said.<P>

"That is on firm legal standing," said Ken Jaques, a spokesman for Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-New Jersey, who first introduced the measure baring misdemeanor spousal abusers from owning guns. "The courts have time and again upheld" similar laws.<P>

DEMOTIONS PLANNED IN L.A.<BR>
So far, at least three Los Angeles County sheriff's deputies have been stripped of their weapons and given 90 days to accept a demotion to a civilian job or get fired, but no Bay Area peace officer has lost his job or had his gun taken away as a result of the law.<P>

A spokeswoman for San Francisco Sheriff Michael Hennessey said the department is reviewing personnel files and has yet to uncover any deputies with domestic violence convictions.<P>

And the S.F. Police Department intends to review the personnel files of its nearly 2,100 officers.<P>

"It looks like we have to comply," said Lt. James Dudley.<P>

Meanwhile, departments are looking to Lungren for guidance on how to proceed.<P>

Deputy Attorney General Paul Bishop, Lungren's point man on gun issues, said his boss has not yet made up his mind on how to advise law enforcement officials.<P>

Police unions are lobbying for a fight with the federal government, but Bishop said Lungren has no plans to challenge the measure in court.<P>

Bishop said Lungren is caught in a political wringer of his own: If Lungren interprets the law narrowly, to include only the most violent of misdemeanors, he risks incurring the wrath of crime victims groups. But if the AG gives it a broad reading to include every domestic violence conviction, he will upset the police.<P>

Said Bishop: "He's in a horrible position."<P>

--<I>Reporter Paul Elias' e-mail address is <a href=mailto:pelias@counsel.com>pelias@counsel.com</a> <P>

The Recorder is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
