<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<H2>Why Can't the Condemned Die Without a Fuss?</H2>

By Ann Woolner<BR>
<I>Fulton County Daily Report</I><BR>
Dec. 23,1996<P>

Attorney General Michael J. Bowers gets a lot of press complaining that the state's most despicable criminals -- those sentenced to die -- are constantly monkeying with the courts to delay justice.<P>

No question that, for most condemned prisoners, the idea is to stay alive as long as possible, and that means manipulating the system to do so.<P>

But what really clogs up the works is when, long after the conviction, long after sentencing, years after the convicted man has been locked into death row and the horror over the original crime has subsided, some judge or panel of judges decides that the guy's trial was unfair in the first place.<P>

Sometimes it happens because of evolving interpretations of death penalty law. But generally it takes a lot to get a conviction set aside -- cooked evidence, racially rigged jury pools, a lawyer literally asleep at the defense table. Yet, depending on whose statistics you use, nearly half to two- thirds of the people Georgia juries have sentenced to die under the modern death penalty law have persuaded one court or another that their trials were so unfair that their sentences or their convictions should be set aside.<P>

But they don't do it without lawyers with time and knowledge and dedication to sift through the court record, the law, the evidence. If anyone knows that, Michael Bowers does.<P>

Fortunately, so does U.S. District Court Judge Willis B. Hunt Jr. Until Hunt put a stop to it, Bowers -- as well as a slim majority of the Georgia Supreme Court -- had been perfectly willing to let Marcus A. Wellons go to his death on Dec. 12 begging for someone to please give him a lawyer, while volunteer lawyers pleaded for the chance to take his case. Indeed, Wellons came within three hours of execution without a lawyer, without even entering -- much less exhausting -- the habeas corpus process the law says he's allowed.<P>

Lawyers for the state say Wellons and the lawyers at Long, Weinberg, Ansley & Wheeler, who had informally agreed to represent him, were merely trying to snake their way around a new state Supreme Court rule that seeks to streamline the habeas process by setting certain deadlines. But in this, the first time Rule 44 has had a workout, the Wellons case shows what's wrong with the rule.<P>

What's wrong is that it assumes the state has enough death penalty appellate lawyers to monitor death row and to work up cases so that they can be prepared to take over from the lawyer handling the inmate's direct appeal and file a state habeas petition the moment the U.S. Supreme Court acts (or decides against acting) on the direct appeal. But last year's federal de-funding of centers set up to handle these appeals (including the now stripped-down Georgia Resource Center), the scarcity of death penalty experts paid by private donations and the dearth of volunteer lawyers has left several Georgians on death row without representation.<P>

Wellons, convicted in the rape and murder of a 15-year-old girl, had barely gotten through the first, automatic round of appeals with a denial of cert from the U.S. Supreme Court on Oct. 7 when two things happened almost simultaneously. Long, Weinberg lawyers, answering a plea from Chief Justice Robert Benham to take a death penalty appeals case pro bono, had just received Wellons' case file on Friday, Nov. 29. That Monday, Dec. 2, Cobb Superior Court Judge Mary E. Staley granted District Attorney Thomas J. Charron's request to order Wellons' execution. She said Wellons should be put to death between Dec. 12 and Dec. 19. Wellons v. Turpin, No. 1:96-cv- 3322 (N.D.Ga. filed Dec. 20, 1995).<P>

With Charron and Staley moving with more speed than is usual in these matters, state officials were caught off guard but hurried to prepare the chair and the condemned for a Dec. 12 execution.<P>

Long, Weinberg lawyers went straight to the Georgia Supreme Court, seeking a stay of execution so they would have time to prepare a habeas petition. Four justices said no, pointing out that the lawyers had skipped a step or two in coming straight to the Supreme Court.<P>

The dissenting justices, Benham, Norman S. Fletcher and Leah J. Sears, said, "Although the Georgia Constitution guarantees the right to seek habeas relief, the complexities of death penalty cases render this right meaningless without competent counsel." Written by Fletcher, the dissenting opinion said the case should be remanded to the appropriate habeas court.<P>

It wasn't, since that was, after all, only a minority opinion. But Wellons and Long, Weinberg lawyers went to federal court and persuaded Hunt to halt the execution until he could hold a hearing on the matter. After the hearing, Hunt issued a 10-month stay and appointed Long, Weinberg counsel for a federal habeas petition -- but only on grounds already exhausted through direct state appeal. This also gives the lawyers time to deal with the state habeas petition on any new grounds they may find.<P>

As the Supreme Court dissenters pointed out, part of the problem is that while the law allows state habeas petitions, no law says the condemned has a right to court-appointed counsel for that phase. Georgia and Mississippi are the only states that do not provide funding for counsel at this stage. Only for trial, direct appeal and the later federal habeas case can the condemned have appointed lawyers.<P>

But what good is a state habeas proceeding without a lawyer?<P>

Not much, which is why Benham is asking for volunteers. And yet, there just are not enough volunteer lawyers to go around, even with the help of the government-funded experts and the Georgia Resource Center.<P>

Things have reached such a pitch in Georgia that we do not have to imagine what it would be like for a death-sentenced convict to show up at a habeas corpus hearing without counsel. We have a transcript.<P>

"Mr. Gibson, do you want to proceed?" Augusta Circuit Superior Court Judge J. Carlisle Overstreet asked the condemned man, Exzavious Gibson, in September at a state habeas corpus hearing held at the state prison at Jackson, which houses death row.<P>

"I don't have an attorney," Gibson replied.<P>

"I understand that."<P>

"I am not waiving any rights," Gibson said.<P>

"I understand that. Do you have any evidence you want to put up?" the judge asked.<P>

"I don't know what to plead," Gibson said.<P>

Overstreet had explained nothing to Gibson about the hearing, except that it was a civil proceeding and that he had a right to counsel, but not to a free one. The judge had also established, by asking the state's lawyer, that Gibson had the burden of proof because he had filed a petition claiming his trial lawyer had been ineffective. But Overstreet did not explain what the burden of proof meant, and he did not tell him this was an evidentiary hearing on the ineffective- assistance claim, or that any issue Gibson failed to raise now would be lost to him forever. Gibson v. Turpin, No. 95-v-648 (Butts Super. filed Dec. 20, 1995).<P>

When Gibson said he did not know how to plead, Overstreet said, "I am not asking you to plead to anything. ... I am just asking you if you have anything you want to introduce to this court."<P>

"But I don't have an attorney."<P>

"Yes, sir. Do you have anything you want to tell this court?"<P>

"I don't waive my rights."<P>

At that point, M. Elizabeth Wells, one of two lawyers left at the Georgia Resource Center, which represents death row inmates and seeks volunteer lawyers for others, stood to introduce herself as the lawyer who had filed motions as amicus curiae in the Gibson case.<P>

The Resource Center, in cases where it has not yet found volunteer counsel, has helped death row inmates file "pro se" habeas petitions while asking for friend of the court status. Wells' precise role in this case is unclear. She did not return a call from the Daily Report.<P>

At the Gibson habeas hearing, she asked to be heard.<P>

"No, ma'am, have a seat," Overstreet said. "Mr. Gibson, do you have anything you want to tell this court?"<P>

"I don't waive any rights."<P>

Addressing the lawyer again, the judge told Wells he had ruled on all her motions. She said she had not seen all the rulings and that the state's lawyer had. Then the judge turned again to Gibson.<P>

"Mr. Gibson, I will be glad to listen to anything you want to tell me, anything you want to say. I judge you have nothing you want to say or nothing you want to tell me. Is that correct? Except what is in your petition."<P>

"I don't have an attorney."<P>

"I know that. I can see that. Does the state want to tell me anything?"<P>

Assistant Attorney General Paige Reese Whitaker told the judge that Gibson had no right to counsel in a state habeas corpus proceeding. She cited case law and noted that the resource center had, in fact, filed motions on Gibson's behalf, if not in his name.<P>

"It is the state's position," Whitaker concluded, "that this is most likely a ploy for an appeal from this habeas corpus proceeding, as the pleadings so far filed by the Resource Center as amicus counsel have threatened that type of an appeal ... ."<P>

Later, Whitaker elaborated in an interview, saying that the Resource Center "chose to make him pro se and make it a test case."<P>

At the hearing, Wells said that simply was not true. Next came a lengthy and remarkably nasty exchange between the judge and Wells. He told her to get into the case or get out of it. She insisted the Resource Center had too large a caseload. He said that maybe if she hadn't taken a two-week European vacation she might have had time to help Gibson. She cited 14-hour workdays and work-filled weekends.<P>

She said she would represent Gibson if the judge gave her enough time to get up to speed. He said she had had plenty of time and that he wouldn't make deals.<P>

She told him he was making a "mockery of the system." He said that, based on what she had filed so far, "I am not so sure you are ... capable of representing him ... ."<P>

"Your Honor, I'm going to try to make you see that this is--that nobody has ever proceeded in a modern death penalty [proceeding] in Georgia without counsel," an exasperated Wells said at one point.<P>

"I understand that," said Overstreet.<P>

The judge invited Wells to represent Gibson, to "come up here and help him."<P>

"Help him what? Help this court deny him all his rights?" she said.<P>

Overstreet told Wells, "All you have done is sit outside the bar and throw stones."<P>

"Your honor--"<P>

"Get inside the bar and do something."<P>

She again asked the judge first to discuss scheduling the case before she agreed, but Overstreet refused.<P>

"Mr. Gibson may as well be hung up from a tree out back," Wells said.<P>

Finally, Overstreet told Wells to be seated and the state's lawyer to proceed. It was the state's turn because Gibson, whose IQ is in the 80s, had offered no evidence to back his claim of ineffective assistance of counsel. He had given no indication that he knows he is supposed to do so.<P>

The state's first and only witness was Gibson's trial attorney, W. Dennis Mullis of Cochran, who represented Gibson as public defender.<P>

Under questioning from Whitaker, Mullis described the rather considerable evidence the state presented at trial when Gibson was convicted of killing an Eastman, Ga., convenience store operator in a robbery, stabbing him so often and so hard that the knife broke off inside the man's body. There was evidence that Gibson, who already had a violent record, robbed the store because of his crack habit. He was 17 at the time of the murder.<P>

Even in this one-sided hearing, it emerged that Gibson's own mother had been murdered, that his father had been absent from his life and the aunt who raised him had abused him, though the degree of abuse was unclear. Mullis presented evidence of Gibson's youth and his troubled childhood during the sentencing phase of the trial to try to dissuade the jury from a sentence of death. To no avail.<P>

Without opposing counsel at the habeas hearing to present evidence, to object, to cross- examine, it's impossible to know whether there is anything in the Gibson case that might have made the difference between life and death. Overstreet hasn't yet ruled in the habeas matter, but certainly from Mullis' direct testimony, he seems to have done a capable job in pursuing various avenues of defense. But then, who knows?<P>

Asked whether he wanted to cross-examine Mullis, Gibson said, "I don't have any counsel."<P>

"I understand that, but I am just asking, can you tell me yes or no whether you want to ask him any questions or not?"<P>

"I'm not my own counsel."<P>

And so, the only witness in the hearing, Mullis, was excused from the witness stand.<P>

At that point, Whitaker said she'd like to ask Gibson the circumstances behind his filing the habeas petition. This brought Wells to her feet. She said such questioning was improper.<P>

"Ms. Wells, Ms. Wells, Ms. Wells," the judge said. "I have warned you once. You stand up again and interrupt these proceedings and I'm going to ask them to escort you out. Do you understand that?"<P>

"[B]ut I cannot sit back and watch this happen--"<P>

"Officer, would you please escort her out of here, please?"<P>

"Mr. Gibson cannot be expected to know what to do in this situation," Wells protested. "He has no attorney."<P>

"Ma'am. Ma'am," the judge said. "You are not helping this man one bit. Please leave."<P>

"Your honor, he has no way of knowing-- "<P>

The judge called a recess and again told an officer to escort Wells out of the courtroom. When court resumed, Whitaker asked Gibson whether he had had any dealings with the Resource Center about filing the habeas petition. Gibson said he did not remember.<P>

Just as Overstreet was about to adjourn, he asked the state's Whitaker whether she knew of "any other<P>

rights or advice we need to give Mr. Gibson ... ."<P>

"I think Mr. Gibson should be aware that this is his first habeas corpus proceeding," said Whitaker, "and that if he chooses to file another one, anything that he doesn't raise in this one is going to probably be found to be waived under Georgia law."<P>

And so it was.r<P>

--<I>Ann Woolner's e-mail address is <a href=mailto:awoolner@counsel.com>awoolner@counsel.com</a>.<P>

Fulton County Daily Report is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
