<TITLE>Court TV News</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<H2>California High Court to Weigh In on Public Access to Civil Trials</H2><P>

By Scott Graham<BR>
<I>The Recorder</I><BR>
Dec. 19, 1996<P>

As the debate rages on over cameras in the courts, the California Supreme Court on Wednesday took up a broader proposition: whether all the media -- and the public as well -- have a constitutional right to attend civil trials. <P>

The Second District Court of Appeal said there is such a First Amendment right, as have at least four federal courts. But the U.S. Supreme Court has never reached the issue -- in fact, the issue of public access to criminal trials badly splintered the court 16 years ago.<P>

The court also agreed Wednesday to try once again to bring some clarity to the statute of limitations in legal malpractice suits. It is the fourth such case the court has agreed to decide this decade.<P>

The courtroom access case, <I>NBC Subsidiary v. Superior Court (Locke)</I>, S056924, stems from a fraud suit against actor Clint Eastwood by his former companion, Sandra Locke. She alleges that he reneged on promises to help her develop motion picture projects, according to the Second District's opinion in the case. <P>

Los Angeles County Superior Court Judge David Schacter ruled that the press and public were welcome for all proceedings held before the jury. But everything else would be held behind closed doors, Schacter ordered, and transcripts of those proceedings would not be made available until after the trial. <P>

Schacter said in court that his paramount concern was a fair trial for the litigants. <P>

"This is the type of information that ends up in tabloids, that faces everybody that walks . . . into a grocery store . . .," Schacter said. "And to ensure that the jurors do not hear this even by accident . . . this is a very, very small intrusion on the First Amendment." <P>

The Second District reversed, relying on the U.S. Supreme Court's 1980 ruling in <I>Richmond Newspapers v. Virginia</I>, 448 U.S. 555. In that case a plurality concluded that because open trials were an essential component of English common law, the First Amendment encompassed such a right. <P>

Although <I>Richmond Newspapers</I> applied only to criminal trials, Second District Justice Paul Turner reasoned -- as have several federal judges before him -- that the same must be true of civil trials. <P>

The superior court in Los Angeles -- which has been an active litigant before the appellate courts recently -- petitioned for review. Frederick Bennett, Los Angeles assistant county counsel, pointed out that <I>Richmond Newspapers</I> was issued by a badly splintered court which expressly reserved the issue of civil trial openness. <P>

Courts construing <I>Richmond Newspapers</I> in the civil context frequently cite a statement from <I>Blackstone's Commentaries</I> that "one of the most conspicuous features of English justice is that all judicial trials are held in open court, to which the public have free access," Bennett noted. <P>

"However," Bennett continued, "Blackstone also noted that the civil law, as then modeled, rejected all public examination of witnesses. . . . For in Ecclesiastical Courts it was invariably the practice to examine the witnesses in secret and to only render the judgment in public." <P>

Bennett also pointed out that in criminal trials, the people, through the prosecution, are a party to the case. "Many civil cases on the other hand arise solely out of private disputes between parties that have resorted to the courts only because they were unable to resolve disputes privately," he argued. And while some civil suits, such as tobacco company litigation for example, may present issues of public importance, the Locke-Eastwood dispute does not, Bennett wrote. <P>

Kelli Sager, a Los Angeles partner at Seattle's Davis Wright Tremaine, representing a media coalition challenging the order, filed a perfunctory eight-page response relying principally on procedural reasons why the court should not grant review. On the merits, she noted simply that the Third, Sixth, Seventh and Ninth Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, as well as some federal district courts, have required that civil trials be open. <P>

"Indeed," Sager wrote, the L.A. Superior Court "has not cited a single case to support the proposition that civil proceedings should not be presumptively open under the First Amendment." <P>

All of the Supreme Court justices except for Stanley Mosk voted to grant review. <P>

BROBECK WINS MALPRACTICE REVIEW<BR>
The Supreme Court also decided Wednesday to wade back into the sticky wicket of legal malpractice statutes of limitations. And it will use two suits against Brobeck, Phleger & Harrison as its vehicle. <P>

Chief Justice Ronald George and Justices Joyce Kennard, Marvin Baxter, Kathryn Mickle Werdegar and Ming Chin voted to grant review in <I>Stone v. Davis</I>, S056567. The same five plus Justice Janice Rogers Brown voted to review <i>Jordache Enterprises v. Brobeck, Phleger & Harrison</i>, S056954. <P>

In <i>Jordache</I>, a blue jeans maker sued Brobeck for failing to advise the company that it had potential insurance coverage in a trade infringement action. In <I>Stone</I>, Brobeck was accused of acting negligently in handling the sale of an office building. In each case, Brobeck is appealing a ruling from the Second District Court of Appeal. <P>

Each case requires the high court to determine when the statute of limitations begins running in a legal malpractice action -- an issue that presents possibly the ugliest morass in California law right now. <P>

The Supreme Court decided four years ago in <I>Laird v. Blacker</I>, 2 Cal.4th 606 (1992), that the statute begins running when an action is dismissed due to an attorney's negligence -- not when all of the appeals from that dismissal are exhausted. <P>

The Supreme Court followed with two rulings over the next three years clarifying and creating exceptions to <I>Laird</I>. Then in November 1995, the court appeared to retreat from the <I>Laird</I> rule in <i>Adams v. Paul</I>, 11 Cal.4th 583. <P>

A splintered ruling issued after the court's 90-day deadline from oral argument, <I>Adams</I> seems to have hopelessly confused what was already a complicated issue.<P>

A sentence from Justice Ramona Godoy Perez's opinion for the Second District in <I>Stone</I> is illustrative: "Nothing in <i>Adams</i> states or even suggests that the <I>ITT</i> court's overruling of <i>Johnson</i> was also being overruled by <I>Adams</i>." <P>

Brobeck played up that confusion in its petitions for review, and invited Justice Chin, who joined the court earlier this year, to resolve it. "Despite this court's best effort to provide guidance in <i>Adams</i> last year, the situation has now degenerated to the point where even panels within the same appellate district openly disagree," Jeffrey Chanin of Keker & Van Nest wrote in the <I>Jordache</i> petition. <P>

"Justice Chin's court of appeal opinions in <I>Foxborough v. Van Atta</I>, 26 Cal.App.4th 217 (1994), and <I>Baltins v. James</I>, 36 Cal.App.4th 1193 (1995), make clear that the accrual question is one in which he has expressed an interest and has offered his own suggestions for harmonizing the relevant cases," Chanin added. <P>

<I>Courts editor Scott Graham's e-mail address is <a href=mailto:sgraham@counsel.com>sgraham@counsel.com</a>.<P>

The Recorder is an affiliate of Court TV.<BR>
Copyright  1996 American Lawyer Media</i><P>

