<TITLE>Court TV News: Cochran, Grace Join Court TV</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<H2>Johnnie Cochran, Nancy Grace Join Court TV</H2>
<P>Court TV announced Nov. 12 that it will launch a live, weeknight talk show, "Cochran & Grace," beginning January 13. The one-hour program will be co-anchored by Atlanta prosecutor Nancy Grace, who specializes in cases involving violent crimes and has never lost a case, and Los Angeles trial and defense lawyer Johnnie L. Cochran, Jr., famed for his trailblazing victories in civil rights cases and work for celebrity clients including Michael Jackson, Reginald Denny and O.J. Simpson.</P>

<P>"Cochran & Grace" will air weeknights at 10:00pm ET and PT (repeated at 1:00am ET and 10:00pm PT) and will be executive-produced by Court TV Executive Vice President and Executive Producer Erik Sorenson. Cochran and Grace, along with high-profile guests, will analyze and debate not only the day's top legal stories, but also the wider social and political implications. The show, featuring viewer call-ins from across the country, will air live from Court TV's New York studios. </P>

<P>Both Cochran and Grace have signed three-year contracts with the network. Grace has resigned as Special Prosecutor of the Fulton County District Attorney's Office and will move to New York. Cochran is continuing to maintain his Los Angeles-based law practice, while dividing his time between New York and Los Angeles.</P>

<P>"In Nancy Grace and Johnnie Cochran we have two highly-regarded, extremely articulate -- indeed electric -- lawyers who have widely different views on most issues but who share an avid interest in the law and how the law is applied in this country and around the world," said Court TV Founder and CEO Steven Brill.</P>

<P>"Most of the shows will be topic and story-driven," said Executive Producer Erik Sorenson, "focusing on topics ranging from the Unabomber trial to the War Crimes Tribunal at The Hague; from race relations in America, to the death penalty, to the right-to-die controversy before the U.S. Supreme Court. Top newsmakers and the movers and shakers of public opinion will join Cochran and Grace every night to discuss the issues of the day."
</P> 
<P>Nancy Grace, born and raised in Macon, Georgia, served as Special Prosecutor on major felony cases for Atlanta's Fulton County District Attorney's Office beginning in 1992 and was Assistant District Attorney from 1987 to 1992.  </P>

<P>Prior to joining the District Attorney's office, Grace practiced civil law as an attorney with the Federal Trade Commission where she pursued complex antitrust violations and nationwide consumer protection cases, and was a judicial law clerk in Federal District Court.  Grace, who has compiled a perfect record of over 55 convictions and no losses, has handled several of Atlanta's most high-profile cases, specializing in serial murder, rape, and molestation. Her most noteworthy convictions include those of Atlanta millionaire Weldon Wayne Carr, convicted for the murder of his wife in a spousal abuse and arson case; David Lindsey Cook, convicted in the murder of his wife after making her death appear to be suicide; Walter Gates, convicted of serial child molestation; and serial rapist Anton Jermaine Smith, convicted of raping several women who then came forward and allowed their names and faces to be publicized. </P>

<P>Grace, who has served as a legal commentator for CNN, NBC Today, CNBC, and Court TV, also is a Litigation Instructor at Georgia State University School of Law and a Business Law Instructor at GSU's School of Business. Grace, a victim's rights advocate, was honored with the Council of Battered Women Award four times and remains a member of the Council on Battered Women Speakers Bureau. She received her undergraduate degree and law degree from Mercer University in Macon, Georgia and was a member of the law review.</P>

<P>Johnnie Cochran was designated one of four "Headliners for 1995" by Time magazine and is the only attorney in California history to be named Trial Lawyer of the Year by organizations representing both the state's civil and criminal attorneys. Cochran began his legal career as a prosecutor with the Los Angeles City Attorney's Office. </P>

<P>After leaving the office, Cochran founded the firm Cochran, Atkins & Evans and, over the next 11 years, established himself as one of the city's leading criminal defense lawyers. In 1978, Cochran returned to public service, when he was appointed Assistant District Attorney of Los Angeles County, making him the first African-American lawyer to hold this position in the country's largest prosecutorial agency. </P>

<P>During his three-year tenure with the office, Cochran spearheaded a reform of the DA's system for handling sexual assault and domestic violence cases. In 1979, he served as founding chairman of Los Angeles County's Domestic Violence Council. Three years later, Cochran returned to private practice as a defense attorney and won a number of landmark decisions in civil rights cases involving police misconduct. In 1992, Cochran won the largest verdict ever against the city of Los Angeles in a police misconduct matter on behalf of a 13-year-old girl molested by a police officer. Cochran has represented such high-profile clients as actor Todd Bridges, former Black Panther Geronimo Pratt, Reginald Denny and O.J. Simpson. </P>

<P>Cochran was named the 1995 "Lawyer of the Year" by The National Law Journal, the first African-American to be so honored. Cochran was recently inducted into the "Inner Circle of Advocates," an exclusive organization limited to 100 of the country's best trial lawyers. Cochran, who was born in Shreveport, Louisiana and educated at Los Angeles High School, UCLA and Loyola Law School, is the author of a personal and professional autobiography, "Journey to Justice," which has been a fixture on the New York Times, Wall Street Journal, Los Angeles Times, and Washington Post bestseller lists since its publication by One World/Ballantine Books in October.</P>



