<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV On The Air</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/ontheair.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/ontheair.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV On the Air" BORDER="0"></A>
<h2>About Court TV</h2>

<P>Court TV is a 24-hour-a-day, 7-day-a-week, cable legal news network and cable programmer dedicated to reporting on the U.S. legal and judicial systems. Court TV began operations on July 1, 1991. It is a joint venture of corporations from both the cable and broadcast television industries, and American Lawyer Media, L.P., the world's largest legal journalism company.<P></P>

<P>Court TV creates all of its own programming and specializes in extended, "gavel-to-gavel" coverage of civil and criminal trials, both live and on tape, supplemented by attorney commentators who explain the proceedings to a lay audience. Court TV's programming, which covers the judicial process not with sound bites but with full, objective reports of the proceedings, has been widely praised as an innovative form of public service television. If you do not get Court TV currently, write or call your cable company and ask for it by name.<P></P>

<P>Court TV's Law Center is THE place online for consumers to get information about what's going on at Court TV as well as what's going on in the law and the legal system. In addition to program guides, court documents, and transcripts of legal proceedings, the Law Center offers practical tips on the law, listings of legal resources, legal games and discussion groups about the law. Members can talk to each other and to the staff at Court TV. Drawing from the resources of Court TV and its affiliate American Lawyer Media, publisher of the award-winning magazine The American Lawyer and nine regional legal publications, the Law Center provides lively, comprehensive coverage of all aspects of the law.</P>

<H3><A NAME="infoline">1-800-COURT56</A></H3>

<P>For more information about Court TV; Court TV has a toll-free menu-driven viewer information telephone number: 1-800-COURT56. Callers can access programming information and verdicts, make comments and ask questions about the network, among other options. 1-800-COURT56 provides pre-recorded listings of each week's daytime, primetime and weekend programming schedules, verdicts of recent trials and information about upcoming trials Court TV is tracking for future coverage. Instructions are also provided on how to receive a Court TV programming guide.<P></P>

<P>The information line also provides instructions for joining Citizens for Court TV, the network's grassroots effort which encourages viewers to lobby for improved camera access laws in their communities. Callers can also leave specific comments or questions regarding Court TV's coverage. Additionally, callers can find out if Court TV is carried on their cable system and if so, on what local channel the network airs.</P>

<P>For more information, read these <a href=ctvfaq.html>Frequently Asked Questions</a> about Court TV.</P>

<H3>Our Partners</H3>

<P>Court TV and the Court TV Law Center work with a number of different organizations, both in broadcast and online. Here are some of our partners.</P>

