<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV On The Air</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/ontheair.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/ontheair.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV On the Air" BORDER="0"></A>
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Court TV</h2>

<H4>When did Court TV start?</H4>

<P>Court TV was launched on July 1, 1991.</P>

<H4>Who owns Court TV?</H4>

<P>Court TV is owned by American Lawyer Media, Liberty Media, NBC and Time Warner.</P>

<H4>What was the first trial on Court TV?</H4>

<P>The first trial was <I>Florida v. Robert Scott Hill.</i>  He was acquitted of charges of murdering his stepmother-in-law more than 20 years earlier.</P>

<H4>How do you select the cases that are covered on Court TV?</H4>

<P>Several factors are considered  when deciding whether to air a trial. They include: how important and interesting the issues in the case are; the newsworthiness of the case and the people involved; the quality and educational value of the trial, and the expected length of the trial.</P>

<H4>Are all of the Court TV anchors also lawyers?</H4>

<P>The on-air anchors are all lawyers with the exception of Terry Moran. He is a journalist who previously worked at <I>Legal Times,</i> a Washington-based affiliate publication of Court TV.</P>

<H4>Will Court TV be closed-captioned?</H4>

<P>Closed captioning is an area that we've recently started exploring. It is something we would like to eventually do but there are tremendous technical obstacles that have to be overcome.</P>

<H4>If Court TV is live, why is there a delay in the broadcast?</H4>

<P>Court TV uses a 10-second delay. This is the policy for all trials. The reason for the delay is to prevent the airing of  information such as the addresses of witnesses, the names of jurors, private conversations between a lawyer and his/her client.</P>

<H4>Are cameras allowed in all courtrooms?</H4>

<P>Most states allow cameras in the courtroom. The exceptions are South Dakota, Indiana and Mississippi.</P>

<P>Most state laws leave it up to the trial judge to decide whether he/she will allow a camera in the courtroom.</P>

<P>The federal courts do not allow cameras. An experiment that allowed cameras in certain federal courts ended and the Judicial Commission, which establishes policy for federal courts, voted not to renew the experiment.</P>

<P>Court TV is working to get the commission to reconsider its ruling.</P>

<H4>What can I do to get Court TV on my cable system?</H4>

<P>There are several steps that can improve the chances of getting Court TV in your viewing area. They are:

<UL>
<LI> Organize a community effort in the form of a letter-writing campaign.
<LI> Urge your mayor and local educators to aid in your efforts.
<LI> Contact your local newspaper and radio call-in show with your plea that
Court TV would benefit the community.
<LI> Call your cable system and request that service be added. Have your
friends call.</UL></P>

<H4>How can I contact Court TV?</H4>

<P>Court TV's toll-free menu-driven viewer information telephone number is <B>1-800-COURT56.</b>  Callers can access programming information and verdicts, make comments and ask questions about the network, among other options. 1-800-COURT56 provides pre-recorded listings of each week's daytime, primetime and weekend programming schedules, verdicts of recent trials and information about upcoming trials Court TV is tracking for future coverage. Instructions are also provided on how to receive a Court TV programming guide.<p></P>

<P>The information line also provides instructions for joining Citizens for Court TV, the network's grassroots effort which encourages viewers to lobby for improved camera access laws in their communities.</P>

<P>Callers also can leave specific comments or questions regarding Court TV's coverage.  Additionally, callers are able to find out if Court TV is carried on their cable system and if so, on what local channel the network airs.</P>
