<h2>The Court TV Schedule</h2>
<h3>Jan. 6 - Jan. 12</h3>


<B>MONDAY JANUARY 6</B><BR>
ALL TIMES ARE EASTERN<P>

9am-1pm<P>

San Rafael, California: Estate of Jerry Garcia v. Carolyn Adams Garcia (Taped) <P>

The widow of Grateful Dead legend Jerry Garcia is contesting a paragraph-long document in which Garcia's second wife, Carolyn Adams Garcia, was granted $5 million of his estate. Carolyn Adams and Jerry Garcia wed in 1981 and separated in 1990. Upon separation both parties drafted and signed a paragraph stating that Garcia would leave Adams a cash settlement of $5 million to be paid over 20 years. When Garcia died in August 1995 his third wife Deborah Koons Garcia contested the agreement, claiming that the paragraph is not an enforceable contract, that Adams and Garcia were not legally married and that Garcia was under the influence of drugs and could not have rationally consented to the agreement. <P>

1pm-1:30pm <P>

Justice Today<P>

A daily news show hosted by Court TV anchor Chris Gordon, providing updates and previews of the day's legal events. <P>

1:30pm-7pm<P>

San Rafael, California: Estate of Jerry Garcia v. Carolyn Adams Garcia (Live) <P>

7pm-7:30pm<P>

Instant Justice<P>

A daily program hosted by Court TV anchor Carol Randolph, highlighting short criminal and civil cases from around the country. Repeated at 10pm.<P>

7:30pm-8pm <P>

Supreme Court Watch<P>

A weekly program that reports solely on the U.S. Supreme Court. Repeated at 10:30pm.<P>

8pm-9pm <P>

Prime Time Justice <P>

"Families v. Simpson" <P>

This nightly special report, which airs during the second half of Prime Time Justice, will include live reports from Court TV reporter Dan Abrams (who will be inside the courtroom during the entire Simpson civil trial), exclusive analysis by host, Terry Moran, and expert guest commentators, and background reports and profiles of the key participants in the trial. Repeated at 11pm. <P>

9pm-10pm <P>

Trial Story <P>

"Stalking: A Mother's Nightmare"<P>

A decorated U.S. Customs Service special agent is charged with aggravated stalking charges for making harassing telephone calls to a woman whose daughter disappeared in the 1970s.<P>

Broadcast:<P>

Court TV: Inside America's Courts<P>

The daily syndicated show features highlights from various cases around the country. Hosted by Court TV anchors Gregg Jarett and Jami Floyd. (Check local listings for channel and time.)<P>

<B>TUESDAY JANUARY 7</B><BR>
ALL TIMES ARE EASTERN<P>

9am-1pm<P>
Brooklyn, New York: New York v. Gheida (Taped)<P>

A bouncer is charged with manslaughter for allegedly pushing a teenager off stage at a rock concert. Eighteen-year-old Christopher Mitchell was engaging in "moshing" a raucous concert ritual sometimes punctuated by participants diving into the audience. Attempting a stage dive, Mitchell was allegedly pushed, landed on his head and died two days later. The bouncer, James Gheida, says he has witnesses who say that Mitchell jumped voluntarily. He claims Mitchell's friends changed their testimony and the prosecutor confused the grand jury in an effort to "railroad" him.<P>

1pm-1:30pm<P>

Justice Today<P>

A daily news show hosted by Court TV anchor Chris Gordon, providing updates and previews of the day's legal events.<P>

1:30pm-7pm <P>

San Rafael, California: Estate of Jerry Garcia v. Carolyn Adams Garcia (Taped) <P>

The widow of Grateful Dead legend Jerry Garcia is contesting a paragraph-long document in which Garcia's second wife, Carolyn Adams Garcia, was granted $5 million of his estate. Carolyn Adams and Jerry Garcia wed in 1981 and separated in 1990. Upon separation both parties drafted and signed a paragraph stating that Garcia would leave Adams a cash settlement of $5 million to be paid over 20 years. When Garcia died in August 1995 his third wife Deborah Koons Garcia contested the agreement, claiming that the paragraph is not an enforceable contract, that Adams and Garcia were not legally married and that Garcia was under the influence of drugs and could not have rationally consented to the agreement. <P>

7pm-7:30pm<P>

Instant Justice<P>

A daily program hosted by Court TV anchor Carol Randolph, highlighting short criminal and civil cases from around the country. Repeated at 10pm.<P>

7:30pm-8pm<P>

Justice Factory<P>

Teen Court TV's fast-paced show which takes viewers behind the scenes of the justice system. This episode: Youth in prison. Repeated at 10:30pm.<P>

8pm-9pm<P>

Prime Time Justice <P>

"Families v. Simpson" <P>

This nightly special report, which airs during the second half of Prime Time Justice, will include live reports from Court TV reporter Dan Abrams (who will be inside the courtroom during the entire Simpson civil trial), exclusive analysis by host, Terry Moran, and expert guest commentators, and background reports and profiles of the key participants in the trial. Repeated at 11pm. <P>

9pm-10pm<P>

Trial Story <P>

"Two Children Dead: Mistake or Murder?"<P>

A woman is charged with two counts of first-degree murder in the deaths of her sons, whom she left strapped in her car while she visited friends.<P>

Broadcast:<P>

Court TV: Inside America's Courts<P>

The daily syndicated show features highlights from various cases around the country. Hosted by Court TV anchors Gregg Jarett and Jami Floyd. (Check local listings for channel and time.)<P>

<B>WEDNESDAY JANUARY 8</B><BR>
ALL TIMES ARE EASTERN<P>

9am-1pm (Alternating Coverage)<P>

Cambridge, Massachusetts: Massachusetts v. Sullivan (Live) <P>

Ralph Sullivan is one of three men charged with first-degree murder in the shooting death of a jewelry store owner. The defendants are accused of committing a string of robberies on jewelry stores in June and July 1994. During a robbery attempt on July 5, Sullivan allegedly shot and killed owner Mark Mariani after a struggle between the two. Sullivan was captured a few days after the murder when he attempted to rob another jewelry store. All three men claim they have alibis and plan on calling witnesses who will testify that they were with the defendants at the time of the crime.<P>

Portland, Oregon: Oregon v. Stangel (Live) <P>

Linda Jean Stangel and her boyfriend, David Wahl, ventured to Astoria, Oregon in November 1995 to discuss problems in their relationship. The day after they arrived, Stangel drove home and alerted Wahl's parents and the Portland police that Wahl had disappeared. Six months later Wahl's badly decomposed body washed up on the coast of Washington state. Stangel was charged with first-degree manslaughter and while in police custody allegedly confessed to pushing Wahl off a 100-foot cliff during an argument. The defense contends that Wahl's death was a tragic accident. <P>

1pm-1:30pm<P>

Justice Today<P>

A daily news show hosted by Court TV anchor Chris Gordon, providing updates and previews of the day's legal events.<P>

1:30pm-7pm (Alternating Coverage)<P>

Cambridge, Massachusetts: Massachusetts v. Sullivan (Live)<BR>
Oregon v. Linda Jean Stangel (Live) Portland, OR<P>

7pm-7:30pm<P>

Instant Justice<P>

A daily program hosted by Court TV anchor Carol Randolph, highlighting short criminal and civil cases from around the country. Repeated at 10pm.<P>

7:30pm-8pm<P>

Justice Factory<P>

Teen Court TV's fast-paced show which takes viewers behind the scenes of the justice system. This episode: Environmental law. Repeated at 10:30pm.<P>

8pm-9pm<P>

Prime Time Justice<P>

"Families v. Simpson"<P>

This nightly special report, which airs during the second half of Prime Time Justice, will include live reports from Court TV reporter Dan Abrams (who will be inside the courtroom during the entire Simpson civil trial), exclusive analysis by host, Terry Moran, and expert guest commentators, and background reports and profiles of the key participants in the trial. Repeated at 11pm.<P>

9pm-10pm<P>

Trial Story<P>

"A Child Dies: Accident or Murder?"<P>

Debra Suzanne Cummings, a 36-year-old mother of three, PTA president and respected member of the community, is charged with second-degree murder and child abuse for the death of Kevin Young, a 9-month-old who she was caring for in an unlicensed baby-sitting service.<P>

Broadcast:<P>

Court TV: Inside America's Courts<P>

The daily syndicated show features highlights from various cases around the country. Hosted by Court TV anchors Gregg Jarett and Jami Floyd. (Check local listings for channel and time.)<P>

