<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV On The Air</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/ontheair.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/ontheair.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV On the Air" BORDER="0"></A>
<H2>Court TV Program Summaries</H2>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/graphics/ctv/programs/instant.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>Airing Monday through Thursday, "Instant Justice" takes viewers 
inside municipal and night courts across the nation for a gritty, 
no-holds-barred look at the judicial system.  From traffic 
violations to disorderly conduct to consumer disputes, the cases 
presented involve real people in dramatic and emotional encounters.
"Instant Justice" is the real People's Court, the real Night Court.  It's an
entertaining glimpse at "bare bones" justice in America today.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><BR></P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/graphics/ctv/programs/dcwatch.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>Court TV's "Washington Watch" is devoted to lively 
discussion about legal news and judicial issues taking place in 
the nation's capital.  This weekly program is hosted by Fred 
Graham, Court TV's chief anchor, who covered the Washington 
political scene and the Supreme Court for CBS News and The New 
York Times.  Expert guests have included U.S. Attorney General 
Janet Reno, former Attorney General Ed Meese and White House 
Counsel Abner Mikva.  Topics have ranged from an analysis of 
President Clinton's crime bill, to the changing face of the U.S. 
Supreme Court, to the state of civil rights issues in the 
Clinton Administration.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><BR></P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/graphics/ctv/programs/verdicts.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>"Verdicts and Justice" is designed for viewers who 
have missed important court decisions and are curious about what 
has happened to the fascinating people whose stories were 
revealed in Court TV trials.  From a look back at the 
extraordinary moments when defendants and other trial 
participants hear the verdict, to reports on the current status 
of those involved in the case, "Verdicts and Justice" gives 
viewers the opportunity to determine the soundness of the 
verdict and learn if justice was served.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><BR></P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/graphics/ctv/programs/tstory.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>"Trial Story" takes the most important moments from a trial covered on Court
TV and condenses them into a one-hour or two-hour prime time program.  From
opening statements to the verdict, Trial Story features all a trial's key
testimony as well as interviews with judges, attorneys, defendants and
plaintiffs.  Some recent "Trial Story" programs include the case of Claire
and Anthony Maglica, a couple whose multi-million dollar business
relationship dissolved along with their 20-year romance, and Dr. Jack
Kevorkian who, in violation of Michigan law, helped terminally ill people
commit suicide.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><BR></P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/graphics/ctv/programs/system.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>Court TV's weekly series "The System" takes viewers on a journey through our
complex, confusing and often misunderstood judicial system.  Set in the
diverse New York City community of Far Rockaway, Queens, "The System" follows
real cases and real characters as they make their way from the street to the
police precinct to the courthouse.  It's the ultimate lesson on how the
judicial process works, outlining legal failures and successes through the
lives of those who are players in the system.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><BR></P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/graphics/ctv/programs/ptj.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>"Prime Time Justice" is a live nightly wrap-up program that highlights the most
important testimony from the day in court and reports on late-breaking legal
news.  Hosted by Court TV's experienced team of anchors, the nightly,
two-hour program features updates on current trials from Court TV's reporters
on location around the country and expert guests who review and analyze trial
highlights.  "Prime Time Justice" is the perfect program for working people
who want to keep up with important trials or for daytime viewers who want
additional perspective on the day's most dramatic testimony.</BLOCKQUOTE>
