<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV On The Air</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/ontheair.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/ontheair.gif" ISMAP
ALT="Court TV On the Air" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>Court TV Trial Story</H2>

<H3>Programs Aired To Date (As of September 17, 1996)</H3>

<H4>To order, call 1-800-888-4580</H4>

<P><B>ARTIS v. WAYSIDE BAPTIST CHURCH<BR>
Abuse of Innocence: Should a Church be Responsible?</B><BR>
Daniel Artis sues Wayside Baptist Church for negligence for hiring and poorly supervising Keith Geren, the church's youth minister, who was convicted of sexually abusing Artis and several other young boys. (7/94)</P>

<P><B>CALIFORNIA v. BARDO - An Act of Obsession: The Death of Rebecca Schaeffer</B><BR>
Robert John Bardo, an obsessed fan, is charged with the 1989 fatal shooting of Rebecca Schaeffer, the actress from the TV series "My Sister Sam." (1/92)</P>

<P><B>CALIFORNIA v. BRANDO - The Christian Brando Story</B><BR>
The sentencing hearing of Christian Brando, who pleads guilty to involuntary manslaughter for the death of his half-sister's boyfriend in California. (91)</P>

<P><B>CALIFORNIA v. BRODERICK - Betty Broderick on Trial: Victim or Criminal?</B><BR>
A San Diego woman is charged with the murder of her ex-husband, a prominent attorney, and his new wife. (2/92)</P>

<P><B>CALIFORNIA v. CHANCE and POWELL<BR>
A Fight for Freedom: A Release Hearing for Clarence Chance and Benny Powell</B><BR>
Seventeen years ago Chance and Powell were convicted of murdering a Los Angeles County Sheriff's deputy and sentenced to life imprisonment. Now, three people who testified against the two say that officers pressured them into lying. (5/92)</P>

<P><B>CALIFORNIA v. CUMMINGS - A Child Dies: Accident or Murder?</B><BR>
Debra Sue Cummings, a 36-year-old mother of three, PTA president and respected member of the community, is charged with second degree murder and child abuse for the death of Kevin Young, a nineteen-month-old whom she was caring for in an unlicensed babysitting service. (11/94)</P>

<P><B>CALIFORNIA v. MENENDEZ - The Menendez Brothers on Trial: The Real Story</B><BR>
A behind-the-scenes look at the trials of Erik and Lyle Menendez, who are charged with murder for the August 1989 shotgun slayings of their parents in the family's Beverly Hills mansion. (5/94)</P>

<P><B>CALIFORNIA v. POWELL, et al. - California v. Powell: What the Jury Saw</B><BR>
The trial of the four Los Angeles police officers accused of police brutality during the arrest of motorist Rodney King. (5/92)</P>

<P><B>CALIFORNIA v. SIMPSON PRE-TRIAL HEARING<BR>
A Question of Evidence: The O.J. Simpson Hearing</B><BR>
A one-hour report on the preliminary hearing in CA v. Simpson. (8/94)</P>

<P><B>CALIFORNIA v. SIMPSON</B><BR>
A four tape series reporting on the trial of O.J. Simpson. (10/95) [Cost per tape is $15.00]</P>

<P><B>COLORADO v. KING - An Inside Job? The Case of a Denver Bank Heist</B><BR>
A former Denver police officer and bank guard is charged with the murders of four security guards which took place during a bank robbery. (9/92)</P>

<P><B>CONNECTICUT v. LIGON - Vietnam Revisited: A Veteran's Nightmare</B><BR>
The trial of Roger Ligon, a Vietnam veteran accused of murder who claims that he suffered from post-traumatic stress disorder. (7/91) [NOT AVAILABLE TO PURCHASE]</P>

<P><B>DODD v. DODD - Dodd v. Dodd: Religion and Child Custody in Conflict</B><BR>
A custody battle from Palm Beach, Florida involving the parents of a young boy. The father claims that the mother, a Jehovah's Witness, is unfit to raise the child because of her religious beliefs (including attitudes toward medical intervention and school sports participation) (12/91)</P>

<P><B>DOE v. KOHN, NAST & GRAF - HIV in the Workplace: Lawyers on Trial</B><BR>
A Philadelphia lawyer sues a law firm for discrimination, claiming he was fired when it was discovered he was HIV positive. (3/95)</P>

<P><B>ENGLAND v. KATIBAH, et al.<BR>
Mistake in the Operating Room: Should the Doctors Pay?</B><BR>
Elizabeth England, 39, sues four Florida doctors for malpractice after she was misdiagnosed with breast cancer and had a mastectomy. (8/94)</P>

<P><B>FENTRESS v. ELI LILLY & CO., et al. - Prozac on Trial</B><BR>
Joseph Wesbecker, who had been diagnosed as mentally ill and had been taking Prozac, returned to the printing plant from which he was on disability leave, shot and killed eight co-workers, wounded 12 others and then killed himself. Five years later, victims and relatives sue the drug manufacturer for product liability. (8/95)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. ALVAREZ - Compassion or Death Sentence?</B><BR>
The Story of Carl Alvarez A Florida man is accused of sexually abusing and murdering his seven-year-old stepson. (6/91)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. CULVER - Broken Trust: A Father Accused of Rape</B><BR>
Asa Culver, 54, stands trial for raping his children almost 25 years ago. (5/93)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. GRIFFIN - Murderer or Avenger?</B><BR>
The Killing of an Abortion Doctor Michael Griffin is charged with first degree murder for the shooting death of Dr. David Gunn during an anti-abortion protest in March 1993. Dr. Gunn performed abortions in northern Florida and Alabama. (6/94)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. GUDINAS - The Murder of Michelle: A Capital Case</B><BR>
Thomas Gudinas is charged with first-degree murder and sexual battery and faces the death penalty. In 1994, he kidnapped Michelle McGrath, 27, from a local bar and beat her to death in an alley; the state's experts say his attention to detail in assaulting McGrath displayed the meticulousness of a serial killer. (7/96)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. HILL - Accused By His Son: The Murder Trial of Robert Scott Hill</B><BR>
A Fort Lauderdale man is charged with the murder of his step mother-in-law over 20 years ago. (10/91)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. KOHUT AND ROURK - Flames of Racism: A Hate Crime in Florida</B><BR>
The trial of two men accused of setting a black tourist from New York on fire. On New Year's Day 1991, three white men abducted Christopher Wilson at gunpoint. Shouting racial slurs, the three covered Wilson with gasoline, set him on fire and left him to burn. (1/94)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. LOEB - A White Supremacist on Trial: Murder or Self Defense?</B><BR>
A self-avowed white supremacist in Florida is charged with murder in the shooting of a black navy veteran after an argument in a parking lot. George Loeb claims he shot Harold Mansfield in self defense; the prosecution claims his hatred for blacks motivated him to kill an unarmed black man. (10/92)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. MARTINEZ-GARCIA<BR>
The AIDS Underground: Breaking the Law for the Greater Good?</B><BR>
A Florida man is accused of illegally dispensing AZT and pain-killers to help AIDS sufferers. Alfredo Martinez-Garcia, who made no money from dispensing the drugs, says he was trying to help AIDS sufferers who were too poor to buy AZT. (3/93)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. NEWTON & NEWTON - Kids and Guns - Who's Responsible?</B><BR>
Ernest and Mona Newton are held criminally responsible after their three-year old son found a loaded gun in their house and shot his two-year-old sister to death. (12/92)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. SMITH - Accused of Rape:</B><BR>
The Trial of William Kennedy Smith. William Kennedy Smith is accused of raping a Florida woman at the Kennedy family compound in West Palm Beach in November of 1991. (1/94)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. TRICE - Self-Defense or Murder:</B><BR>
A Husband on Trial Charles Trice, Jr. is charged with burglary and first degree murder for the death of his second wife, Darla. Trice maintains that he shot Darla in self-defense after she stabbed him with a knife. (2/96)</P>

<P><B>FLORIDA v. WUORNOS - Aileen Wuornos - Serial Killer or Victim?</B><BR>
A woman is charged with murdering a man after soliciting him for sex. She admits to six other similar killings, but claims they were all in self-defense. (7/92)</P>

<P><B>FLYNN v. GOLDMAN SACHS - Fired on Wall Street: A Case of Sex Discrimination?</B><BR>
Joanne Flynn's sex discrimination suit against Goldman Sachs, the prestigious Wall Street investment firm. (2/94)</P>

<P><B>GEORGIA v. CARR - The Death of Patricia Carr: Accident or Arson?</B><BR>
Weldon Wayne Carr, owner of the country's largest seed catalogue, is charged with murder and arson in the death of his wife who died from smoke inhalation from a fire in their home. (6/95)</P>

<P><B>GEORGIA v. CASSOTTA - Cop on Trial: Scapegoat or Murderer?</B><BR>
Maurice Cassotta, a local policeman, is accused of killing his former girlfriend and their 2-year-old son. (10/95)</P>

<P><B>GEORGIA v. CHAPEL - The Murder of Emogene: Is a Cop to Blame?</B><BR>
Former Police Officer Mike Chapel is charged with killing Emogene Thompson, whose burglary case he was investigating, and stealing the remainder of her money. He faces the death penalty. (6/96)</P>

<P><B>GEORGIA v. LEGARE - Should Andrew Legare Live or Die?</B><BR>
Legare was 17-years-old when he was sentenced to death in Georgia. He has been on death row for 15 years, and in this sentencing hearing he asked that his death penalty be overturned and changed to life imprisonment. (4/92)</P>

<P><B>GEORGIA v. REDDING - A Rapist on Trial: DNA Takes the Stand</B><BR>
Kenneth Redding is charged with the rape and aggravated assault of two women. The women were unable to identify their attacker by sight, but after seven years and several near-dismissals, Redding was indicted for the crimes solely on the basis of DNA evidence. (1/95)</P>

<P><B>GREGORY K v. RALPH K, et al. - Families Divided: A Child's Day in Court</B><BR>
The case of Gregory K, an 11-year-old boy who seeks a "divorce" from his parents so he can be adopted by his foster parents. (1/93)</P>

<P><B>HALL v. HALL - Irretrievably Broken: A Divorce Lawyer Goes to Court</B><BR>
The divorce trial of Harry Hall, a prominent divorce lawyer, and his wife, a former client. Jacqueline Hall claims her husband is an alcoholic and has a habit of becoming sexually involved with his clients. Among those clients is his current mistress, Jacqueline Hall alleges. She is asking for divorce on the grounds of adultery. (11/93)</P>

<P><B>IN RE CUSTODY OF BABY GIRL CLAUSEN<BR>
Child of Mine: The Fight for Baby Jessica</B><BR>
The case of a Michigan couple who attempted to adopt a baby in February 1991 and the child's biological parents from Iowa. (4/93)</P>

<P><B>IN RE MICHAEL MARTIN - To Live or Die? A Family Battles Over Life Support</B><BR>
The trial of a Michigan woman who wants the court to discontinue the intravenous feeding of her husband, Michael Martin, whose injuries in a 1987 car crash left him partially paralyzed and brain-damaged. (11/93)</P>

<P><B>IOWA v. MORGAN - Evidence Suppressed, Justice Denied?</B><BR>
The case of a young man charged with the murder of his adoptive parents in Iowa. (91)</P>

<P><B>KAPLAN v. CHAMBERLAIN<BR>
Battle for a Surrogate Baby: Who are the Better Parents?</B><BR>
The custody trial involving Susan Chamberlain, a 26-year-old surrogate mother who agreed to be artificially inseminated in exchange for $25,000, and Joseph Kaplan, the biological father of the three-month-old child. (10/93)</P>

<P><B>KENTUCKY v. ENGLISH - Alleged Abuse, Definite Murder: The Trial of Tracy English</B><BR>
The trial of a Kentucky teenager accused of murdering her father. Tracie English claims there was a history of sexual abuse and that her father was attempting to rape her at the time she shot him. (8/91)</P>

<P><B>MAGLICA v. MAGLICA - Broken Hearts, Broken Commitments</B><BR>
A breach of contract case in which Claire and Anthony Maglica, who lived and worked together for more than twenty years, fight over the assets of a multi-million dollar flashlight business, Mag Instrument. (8/94)</P>

<P><B>MASSACHUSETTS v. CARON - Accident or Abuse? A Babysitter on Trial</B><BR>
A Massachusetts woman is accused of violently shaking a baby to death. She claims she was attempting to revive the baby who had stopped breathing.(6/92)</P>

<P><B>MASSACHUSETTS v. CROSS - Statutory Rape: A Woman Accused</B><BR>
The trial of a female teacher in Cambridge, Massachusetts charged with the statutory rape of a 15-year-old student. (10/91)</P>

<P><B>MASSACHUSETTS v. FULLER - A Teenage Killing: Jealousy or Drugs?</B><BR>
A 17-year-old Massachusetts boy is on trial for the murder of his 14-year-old girlfriend. The defense claims his use of alcohol and steroids drove him to violence. (2/93)</P>

<P><B>MASSACHUSETTS v. MANNING - Commonwealth v. Manning: Priest v. Priest</B><BR>
Highlights from the trial in which a priest is accused of sexually molesting and assaulting an 11-year-old altar boy. (1/95)</P>

<P><B>MASSACHUSETTS v. TROISI, et al. - A Prostitute's Word: Was it Rape?</B><BR>
Four young men are charged with the kidnapping of a prostitute in Lowell, MA. (2/94)</P>

<P><B>MICHIGAN v. KEVORKIAN - Michigan v. Kevorkian: The Trial of Dr. Death</B><BR>
A report on the trial of Jack Kevorkian, who is charged with a felony for assisting in the suicide of Thomas Hyde, a 30-year-old man suffering from Lou Gehrig's disease. This is the first courtroom battle ever over the right to die. (10/94)</P>

<P><B>MICHIGAN v. VRIESENGA - Was It An Accident? A Death on Halloween</B><BR>
The trial of a Michigan man charged with manslaughter in the death of a teenager on Halloween night. (8/93)</P>

<P><B>MISSOURI v. NEELEY - A Father Kills: Murder or Insanity?</B><BR>
Paul Neeley is charged with murder in the killing of his former best friend, Mike Terrell. Neeley shot Terrell hours after his 16-year-old daughter told him that Terrell had raped her four years earlier. (4/95)</P>

<P><B>MOSELEY v. GENERAL MOTORS - A Son's Death: Is GM at Fault?</B><BR>
The lawsuit filed by an Atlanta couple whose 17-year-old son was burned to death after his GM truck was broadsided in a collision. (5/93)</P>

<P><B>NEW HAMPSHIRE v. SMART - Pam Smart's Calculated Crime of Passion</B><BR>
A New Hampshire school teacher is charged with conspiring with her teenage lover to murder her husband. (9/91)</P>

<P><B>NEW JERSEY v. BIAS - A Husband's Defense: Suicide, Not Murder</B><BR>
A Belvidere, New Jersey man is charged with murdering his wife of five years, claiming he was trying to disarm her during a suicide attempt. (1/92)</P>

<P><B>NEW YORK v. BURROUGH, et al. - Caught in the Crossfire: Death of a Local Hero</B><BR>
The trial of three teenagers accused of murder in the killing of school principal Patrick Daly in a Brooklyn housing project. Daly, who was searching for a delinquent student who had skipped school, was shot to death when he stumbled into a shootout involving three alleged drug dealers. (9/93)</P>

<P><B>NEW YORK v. FERGUSON - Murder on the 5:33</B><BR>
The Trial of Colin Ferguson Colin Ferguson, who defends himself, is accused of killing 6 people and wounding 19 aboard a Long Island Railroad commuter train in December 1993. (1/96)</P>

<P><B>NEW YORK v. MCKIEVER - New York v. McKiever: Murder to Manhattan</B><BR>
Kevin McKiever stand trial for the murder of former Rockette Alexis Welsh in New York. (6/95)</P>

<P><B>NEW YORK v. NELSON - A Community Torn: A Killing in Brooklyn</B><BR>
The case of Lemrick Nelson, a black teenager charged with the stabbing death of a Hasidic Jewish scholar, a bystander during a riot in Crown Heights, New York. Violence erupted in this Brooklyn, New York neighborhood after a Jewish driver's car jumped the sidewalk and killed a seven-year-old black child. (2/93)</P>

<P><B>NORTH CAROLINA v. HUNT, GARDONE & WATKINS<BR>
Gay Bashing or Self Defense? Three Marines on Trial</B><BR>
The trial of three U.S. Marines charged with misdemeanor assault for allegedly beating up a patron of a Wilmington, North Carolina gay bar. The incident occurred during the debate surrounding President Clinton's proposal to lift the ban on gays and lesbians in the military. (6/93)</P>

<P><B>NORTH DAKOTA v. MONSERUD - Abortion Protest: America's Battlefront</B><BR>
The trial of anti-abortion protestors who locked themselves to a Fargo, North Dakota health clinic that performs abortions. (10/91)</P>

<P><B>NORTHSIDE PARTNERS v. PAGE AND NEW KIDS ON THE BLOCK<BR>
New Kids' in Court: Is Their Hit Song a Copy?</B><BR>
Tommy Page and New Kids on the Block, who co-wrote the song "I'll Be Your Everything," are sued for copyright infringement by the writer of a song by the same title recorded almost two decades ago. (1/93)</P>

<P><B>NUREMBERG TRIAL - The Nuremberg Trial</B><BR>
A one-hour summary of the 1945 Nuremberg Trial in which an International Military Tribunal consisting of judges from the United States, England, France and the Soviet Union tried 22 key Nazi Party members on charges of war crimes and crimes against humanity. (5/96)</P>

<P><B>OHIO v. BANKS - Alleged Date Rape: A College Athlete on Trial</B><BR>
A former University of Cincinnati basketball star is charged with the sexual assault of three students. (11/91)</P>

<P><B>RANDOM HOUSE v. GEMINI STAR PRODUCTIONS<BR>
Joan Collins: Actress, Author, Defendant</B><BR>
Random House sues actress and writer Joan Collins and her production company for breach of contract. The publishing house claims it signed a contract with Collins to write two novels, but she never delivered complete manuscripts. The company is suing for a return of its advance. Collins maintains that she submitted two finished manuscripts and is countersuing for additional advances. (8/96)</P>

<P><B>RODRIGUEZ v. BUICE - A Hate Crime in Houston: A Mother Seeks Justice</B><BR>
A woman sues two men for the wrongful death of her son, who was fatally stabbed by a gang of young men in an anti-gay hate crime. The two defendants maintains that they were merely bystanders and therefore not liable. The plaintiff claims the attackers acted in concert and share responsibility, because those cheering from the sidelines helped cause the violence. (1/96)</P>

<P><B>SCHALLOCK v. HEINZE, et al.<BR>
A Question of Conduct: Sexual Harassment or Consent?</B><BR>
A 26-year-old female attorney claims that her former boss, the executive director of the Arizona Prosecuting Attorneys' Advisory Council (APAAC), is guilty of sexual harassment and that APAAC did not properly supervise the office. (3/92)</P>

<P><B>TEJO v. BLOSHINSKY - A Doctor's Fault or a Woman's Fate?</B><BR>
The story of a New York woman's suit against a doctor and a hospital in connection with the diagnosis and subsequent modified radical mastectomy she received after being told four months earlier that a mammogram's results were inconclusive. (8/92)</P>

<P><B>TENNESSEE v. DUCKER - Two Children Dead: Mistake or Murder?</B><BR>
A woman is charged with two counts of first-degree murder in the deaths of her sons, whom she left strapped in her car while she visited friends. (3/96)</P>

<P><B>TEXAS v. BROSKY -- A Skinhead on Trial</B><BR>
The trial of Christopher Brosky, charged with conspiracy in the allegedly racially motivated murder of Donald Thomas, a 32-year-old black man. (3/94)</P>

<P><B>TEXAS v. GRIFFIN - A Fatal Dose, A Child's Death</B><BR>
A Texas mother is charged with "injury to a child by omission" after her five-year old son died from the effects of alcohol poisoning. The mother did not seek medical help until fourteen hours after he passed out and began convulsing and having seizures. (11/91)</P>

<P><B>TEXAS v. RAILEY - Did Reverend Railey Strangle His Wife?</B><BR>
The trial of the former Dallas minister accused of the near-fatal choking of his wife five years ago. Walker Railey's wife is in a chronic vegetative state. (6/93)</P>

<P><B>TWIGG v. MAYS - Switched at Birth: The Custody Case of Kimberly Mays</B><BR>
The custody battle over 14-year-old Kimberly Mays who was switched with another child at birth. Ernest and Regina Twigg asked a judge to declare Kimberly their biological daughter and to award them visitation rights. Kimberly asked that the Twiggs' parental rights be terminated and that she be allowed to remain with the man who raised her. (10/93)</P>

<P><B>VAN HOUTEN PAROLE HEARING<BR>
Ready For Release? A Manson Murderer's Parole Hearing</B><BR>
Leslie Van Houten, convicted in 1969 for her role in the "Manson Family" murders, claims to have given up her ties to the Manson family and become a model prisoner. The parole board must decide whether Van Houten is suitable for release. (4/92)</P>

<P><B>VERMONT v. GRACE - A Battered Woman's Defense: Fear, Not Anger</B><BR>
Christine Grace is charged with the murder of her abusive boyfriend in Vermont and uses a battered woman's defense. (91)</P>

<P><B>VIRGINIA v. BOBBITT - Assault, Revenge or Self-Defense? The Trial of Lorena Bobbitt</B><BR>
Lorena Bobbitt, a 24-year-old manicurist, is charged with malicious wounding for dismembering her husband John. (4/94)</P>

<P><B>WASHINGTON v. SOUSA - Parents on Trial: Was it Murder?</B><BR>
The trial of a 27-year-old Seattle woman accused of murder in the scalding death of her five-week-old baby. Prosecutors say she got drunk and dunked the baby into a sink full of nearly boiling water. Her husband was charged with manslaughter for letting it happen. The parents claim the death was a tragic accident. (8/93)</P>

<P><B>WEEKS v. BAKER & MCKENZIE - The Price of Harassment: A Law Firm on Trial</B><BR>
Rena Weeks, a former secretary at the Baker & McKenzie law firm, sues the firm and attorney Martin Greenstein for sexual harassment. (11/94)</P>

<P><B>ZION v. NEW YORK HOSPITAL - Deadly Dosage: Who's at Fault?</B><BR>
Journalist Sidney Zion sues New York Hospital for the wrongful death of his daughter. (5/95) </P>

