<HEAD>

<TITLE>Teen Court TV: Your Turn</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">



<P align=center> <A HREF="/teens/maps/tbuttons.map"><IMG SRC="/teens/graphics/theadyt.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></P>

<br clear=all><P>



<H2>Your Turn</H2>



<H3>Teen Curfew:  Necessary or Unconstitutional?</H3>



<P>Okay, you've accepted the fact that your parents tell you when to come home, but now you have to listen to politicians? Shouldn't teenagers have the same rights as everyone else? What's the point of learning about the Constitution in class if it doesn't apply to you? Yet another source of torment for the already angst-ridden teenage years. </P>



<P>This week we will go to San Diego to discuss teen curfews.  We'll discuss whether curfew laws violate the constitutional rights of teenagers.  We'll also think about whether cities can legally use curfew laws to keep teens off the streets as a way to cut down on crime.</P>



<P>In 1994, the San Diego City Council adopted a proposal for stricter enforcement of the city's existing juvenile curfew ordinance.  San Diego has had a juvenile curfew ordinance since the 1940s, but it was rarely enforced.  The new curfew bars teens from hanging-out after 10 p.m. If you get caught and your parents don't come for you, you'll be stuck at the police station until the sun comes up. The exceptions to the rule are if a teen is with a parent or guardian, on an emergency errand for a parent, returning from a school sponsored activity, or from a job.</P>



<P>Case in point: Asha Settimo was out on a date, with her mom's permission, when she was picked up by the San Diego police.  Asha spent two hours at the police station before being released.</P>



<P>Asha thought this law was so unfair that she joined other teenagers in a lawsuit filed by the American Civil Liberties Union. The ACLU argues that the benefit of any small reduction in crime is far outweighed by claims that the curfew violates minors' first and fourteenth amendment rights and works as an unconstitutional mandate of guilt by association.</P>



<P>David Pressman, a 19-year old college student and one of the teenagers joined in the lawsuit, says that the curfew forces law-abiding teenagers to consider breaking the law even if they are going to a study group or a production of Hamlet. He also argues that crime during curfew hours has decreased at the same rate as non-curfew hours.  </P>



<P>Others think a curfew is worthwhile if it prevents teens from getting killed and lowers the crime rate. Mayor Susan Golding credits teen curfews for the 20 percent drop in violent juvenile crime in San Diego from 1992 to 1995.  In addition, she says that the number of juvenile victims of violent crimes has dropped 25 percent, and the number of juvenile victims of violent crimes during curfew hours has dropped 40 percent from 1993 to 1995.</P>



<P>While an appellate court in California decides whether the night time curfew law is constitutional, San Diego is cranking up the heat by adopting a daytime curfew which fines students up to $250 for skipping school for their first offense and requires them to perform community service. </P>



<BLOCKQUOTE>
<IMG SRC="/teens/graphics/bullet.gif" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0> <B>Tell us what you think about censorship:</B> <A HREF="/teens/quizzes/surcurfew.html">Take our survey.</A><P>
